@220  = ~[ARAN] Do you want to come up an' help tuck me in?~
@221  = ~[WWENCH] I prefer real men, not boys who need to be mothered. But I will have the kitchen send up some warm milk and cookies.~
@222  = ~[ARAN] I'd enjoy myself a mite more if that Firewine made it over my direction...~
@223  = ~[WWENCH] Show me some coin, and I could make sure some came your way, sirrah.~
@224  = ~[ARAN] Now then, I can handle Pugney right fine. Stop an' chat a moment, eh?~
@225  = ~[WWENCH] You are welcome to handle him any way you want. But I have to keep on about my work.~
@226  = ~[ARAN] Why not handle me, instead o' him? I have a good bit  to handle, you know.~
@227  = ~[WWENCH] I will tell you what I tell him - you do not have a handle big enough to do the job correctly.~
@228  = ~[ARAN] Wild beasts, meanin' four legged, two legged, an' th' occasional mercenary out for a brawl, eh?~
@229  = ~[ARAN] Bloody hells - I don't have a quill sharpened. If this be havin' some meanin', someone remember this, eh? I can write it down later.~
@230  = ~[ARAN] Xvim's Spit, if there be anythin' more ugly than bein' called cattle by a bloodsucker, I don't rightly know what it is. Someone get me a stake.~
@231  = ~[ARAN] Well, now, for a minute there, I was a mite worried. I thought we was about to...~
@232  = ~[ARAN] Bloody well kill me before I get to that point, eh? I don't want to retire like that. I'd be right happy to go out in combat instead o' whitherin' away.~
@233  = ~[YARIN] You are an arrogant bastard, young feller.~
@234  = ~[ARAN] Aye, back in th' olden days, you'd smile an' bow while slittin' their throats, eh?~
@235  = ~[YARIN] We did things right, back then. Smooth as silk.~
@236  = ~[ARAN] <PRO_HESHE> scrubs up well, that be for sure. Even pays <PRO_HISHER> taxes an' tithes, gods help <PRO_HIMHER>.~
@237  = ~[LATHANDERITE] Would that more of the world followed the path of Light, as you do.~
@238  = ~[ARAN] Looks can be deceivin', eh? But <PRO_HESHE> can get what needs doin' done right.~
@239  = ~[LATHANDERITE] Would that more of the world followed the path of Light, but sometimes Lathander works in mysterious ways.~
@240  = ~[ARAN] So, you mean for us to show them th' sharp edge o' the sword, an' make sure they are not about to get revived, eh?~
@241  = ~[TALOSITE] The Wrath of Talos must be rendered, of course.~
@242  = ~[ARAN] An' by 'find', you mean show them th' sharp edge o' the sword, eh?~
@243  = ~[HELMITE] See that justice is done, whatever form that may take. Helm sees all.~
@244  = ~[ARAN] You know, th' only problem wi' mercenary work is that sometimes you end up bein' th' sharp end for a right set o' bastards, eh? It ends up bein' a matter o' who's coin be th' best deal.~
@245  = ~[BODHI] Then you will be interested in my proposition.~
@246  = ~[ARAN] An' you say I talk too much. What say we just kill this arrogant bloodsucker an' be done wi' it?~
@247  = ~[ARAN] That be a huge sum o' coin, for a simple contract, <CHARNAME>. I'd put some funds aside for resurrection an' restoration. I never did see a high priced contract where the client told the whole story.~
@248  = ~[FIRKRAG] Indeed, my offer is generous to a fault. I merely wish to pay for the best, and have the job done correctly the first time.~
@249  = ~[ARAN] That be th' biggest damned thing I have ever seen. Are we goin' to fight *him*?~
@250  = ~[ARAN] I told you that were too much coin for a simple contract. That's the biggest damned thing I have ever seen. We are goin' to fight *him*?~
@251  = ~[KELDORN] Ten feet. That is very tall. Do you know how tall that really is?~
@252  = ~[KORGAN] Ten feet. Very tall. Very, very tall.~
@253  = ~[VALYGAR] Ten feet. That is very tall. Do you know how tall that really is?~
@254  = ~[CERND] Ten feet. That is very tall. Do you know how tall that really is?~
@255  = ~[ARAN] Tiamat's Twisting Tentacles, it's bloody well ten feet.~
@256  = ~[JAHEIRA] He is actually 10 feet 9 inches.~
@257  = ~[EDWIN] He is actually 10 feet 9 inches. (Rube. We are engaging a dragon, and he jests about size.)~
@258  = ~[ARAN] But it's those last 9 inches that'll kill you.~
@259  = ~[AERIE] He - He's huge... he is three elves high.~
@260  = ~[VICONIA] He is easily three Drow high - a magnificent specimen, and a fitting sacrifice.~
@261  = ~[KELDORN] He sounds more impressive at 10 feet 9 inches.~
@262  = ~[KORGAN] 10 feet 9 inches sounds more fancy.~
@263  = ~[VALYGAR] He sounds more impressive at 10 feet 9 inches.~
@264  = ~[CERND] He sounds more impressive at 10 feet 9 inches.~
@265  = ~[MINSC] That is a big but-kicking task. My boot may not be large enough.~
@266  = ~[BOO] *squeak*!~ [GAM_48]
@267  = ~[MINSC] Boo thinks I should use my sword, not my boot.~
@268  = ~[ARAN] All right, I'm stickin' wi' 10 feet 9 inches, includin' those fangs. Now, how many of what kind o' thing would we have to line up end to end to get a practice run at this?~
@269  = ~[FIRKAAG] Very amusing. Perhaps I shall tell your spirits exactly how many of your crisping bodies I had to stack up to match my height.~
@270  = ~[ARAN] This is the part where you stop talkin', an' we smile, an' then you smile, an' then you get chopped up into liiitle teensy-teensy pieces and served wi' a dry Chianti FR 1276. Preferably chilled.~
@271  = ~[IMOEN] Hey, Aran, when did you get all fancy, with yer 'Chianti FR 1276' an' all?~
@272  = ~[ARAN] Well, you see a fancy-pants mage, and you get all wordy. Goes with the territory, I guess.~
@273  = ~[KORGAN] Bugger the wine. But you be owin' me a keg o' Traskan Ale when I kill him first.~
@274  = ~[ARAN] Make it a bet, then. Two bottles FR 1276 if I kill the Cyric-buggerin' bastard, a keg to you if you get in there first.~
@275  = ~[KELDORN] Well and finely stated, my friend. But let us not waste more breath. We shall need it to destroy this foul creature.~
@276  = ~[ARAN] Sounds like a plan to me. You take th' high road, an' I'll take th' low road, an' I'll be in th' cen-ter, a-fore ye!~
@277  = ~[ARAN] Minsc, my friend, you want t' wager which one o' us clobbers him first?~
@278  = ~[MINSC] Boo says that we should wager afterward, with dice made from his tail-bone. Then every time we kick the dice, we will be BUTT-KICKING FOR GOODNESS!~
@279  = ~[AERIE] That is disgusting, Aran. Kill him and eat him? How can you say such horrible things. I - I thought I knew you.~
@280  = ~[ARAN] Aerie, m'dear, it were a joke. Gallows humor, an' all that. We are just going to kill him, not gnaw on his bones, or anythin'. Just tryin' to rattle him a little. Understand?~
@281  = ~[AERIE] Oh, I understand. Irenicus, you will fall before us, and we shall... we shall... nibble your bum!~
@282  = ~[ARAN] Closer, anyways, Aerie. Though I think we were goin' more for the 'fearsome foe' than the 'perilous rabid bunny rabbit' approach. But let's go wi' it.~
@283  = ~[ARAN] Jaheira, do you want in on th' action? A little side bet on who takes fancy-pants over there an' tears him a new arsehole?~
@284  = ~[JAHEIRA] I think not. I have spent so much time watching you talk, that I have decided to see if it really works.~
@285  = ~[ARAN] See if what really works?~
@286  = ~[JAHEIRA] I am attempting to determine if you can actually succeed in talking him to death.~
@287  = ~[IRENICUS] I think I shall enjoy this, if only to SHUT YOU IMBECILES UP!~
@288  = ~[ARAN] Nice voice. The rest o' th' package, not so nice, eh?~
@289  = ~[ARAN] Sune's Left Br... err... hey, come on over here, lass, an' I will protect you right fine.~
@290  = ~[ARAN] Sune's Left Br... err... sorry. Big change. Hey, give us a spin, eh, so we can check you are all in one piece an' OK?~
@291  = ~[ARAN] Sune's Breath... I just got me a mental picture I should keep to myself, eh?~
@292  = ~[ARAN] Centuries o' history be reason enough.~
@293  = ~[ARAN] Bloody hells, girl. That look could melt mithral. Turn that gaze my way some time, eh?~
@294  = ~[ARAN] Bloody hells, girl. That look could melt mithral. Looks like someone's libido just woke up, eh? They hit puberty so fast these days...~
@295  = ~[ARAN] I suppose this be a bad time to joke about every-body needs some-body, eh?~
@296  = ~[VALYGAR] Yes.~
@297  = ~[ARAN] Drow. Enough said. Let's move on, eh? I am gettin' a mite hungry.~
@298  = ~[ARAN] I say she comes along right proper. Tell you what, she can walk right in front o' me, an' then I'd be there to keep an eye on her bu... err... keep an eye on her, eh?~
@299  = ~[ARAN] I say she comes along right proper. It never did hurt to have a friend on th' inside, eh? Beats stormin' a castle with no map an' gettin' slaughtered through th' murder holes.~
@300  = ~[ARAN] Bloody good to see you, Yoshimo, though my purse be a bit fuller when there be less o' your dice in use, eh?~
@301  = ~[YOSHIMO] I shall be happy to help you find a lighter path again, my friend.~
@302  = ~[ARAN] Talos' Fickle Breath, <CHARNAME> be droppin' you in an' out o' th' party a good bit. Is this stay permanent, or is <PRO_HESHE> just messin' wi' you?~
@303  = ~[YOSHIMO] I will leave that to <PRO_HISHER>'s discretion, my friend.~
@304  = ~[ARAN] *snort* *cough*~
@305  = ~[YOSHIMO] You are not helping, my friend.~
@306  = ~[ARAN] Useful as all hells when a brawl breaks out, but you'd think that th' bastards would draw a line someplace. A friendly brawl or a little magic use be a sight less harm than drugs, slavery, an' such.~
@307  = ~[YOSHIMO] Coin rules much of the world, my friend. It is the way of all things.~
@308  = ~[ARAN] Shar's Spit, Yoshimo, there be no need to insult all this slime like that. It' be ashamed to be close to a Drowess.~
@309  = ~[ARAN] HAH! Yoshimo, you wag! Good 'un.~
@310  = ~[ARAN] Yeah, well, my purse be a mite lighter, too. You have a way wi' th' cards, you do, Yoshimo.~
@311  = ~[ARAN] (snort) You got a gift for a mite bit o' understatement, eh? Last poor bastard I done heard about got delivered back to th' lovin' embrace o' his family, slow-like. First a finger, then a toe, then an eye...~
@312  = ~[ARAN] Bloody traitor - Ilmater's mercy be not for th' likes o' you.~
@313  = ~[YOSHIMO] I have less choice then you think.~
@314  = ~[ARAN] A geas - you know better than to take that kind of contract. Now you are forsworn on two fronts. Bastard.~
@315  = ~[YOSHIMO] Sometimes there is no choice.~
@316  = ~[ARAN] If that be th' case, every blighted soldier what ever walked Toril is in a right bit o' trouble. Dead be dead, an' we didn't know better. Only one thing left to do - go through their pockets an' look for spare coin. An' mayhap find a clue as to what adversary done did this to us.~
@317  = ~[ANOMEN] I expected no better from you. You have no concept of honor. This is a conversation for your betters, sellsword.~
@318  = ~[ARAN] Talos' Treacherous Tongue, you do go on about bile an' such. For a chivalrous man, you throw words like 'slattern' an' 'trollop' an' such. I though chivalry was supposed to be better than that.~
@319  = ~[ANOMEN] Any creature that has thrown away the gifts of the gods and allows themselves to sink to such depravity should be cleansed from Toril, not given the respect reserved for a true lady.~
@320  = ~[ARAN] Shiny metal armor, shiny metal heart, eh? I'll stick to my on beliefs on that one, I think.~
@321  = ~[ANOMEN] You do not think, Whitehand. And as for your beliefs, I pray to Torm and Helm that you find some.~
@322  = ~[ARAN] Errr.. crap. An' here I thought it were just survival in a cold, cruel world. See what comes o' not havin' a righteous upbringin'? I get all my values all confused, like. I've just been waitin' for some wet-behind-th' ears follower o' Torm to come along an' tell th' whole world what be right an' what be wrong, an' set us all straight.~
@323  = ~[ARAN] I be fine wi' the whole atonement thing, but temperance? I think I'd find me a more forgivin' god, eh?~
@324  = ~[ANOMEN] I was not speaking to you, Whitehand. Go drown your sorrows in drink, and perhaps you will drown mine there as well.~
@325  = ~[ARAN] That be what I did. Worked out fine, too. On account o' most military folks be right reasonable sorts, an' good at th' card games an' drinkin'. Holy orders, well, they fight fine, but not so much on th' drinkin' an' card games, eh?~
@326  = ~[ARAN] Too true. I think we should give 'em a good drink, an' perhaps instruct them on how to fight a bit. Give 'em good, clean, respectable livin', fightin' th' good fight for us.~
@327  = ~[ANOMEN] Perhaps as an inducement to service, a drink. And perhaps train them to be productive member of society.~
@328  = ~[ARAN] Right. I bet we could get a bunch o' them together, an' with th' right trainin', they might be able to be a decent fightin' force. Then, we could go around an' kick seedy bastards o' nobles who think they are better than everyone else, an' their crap don't stink, an' teach 'em manners.~
@329  = ~[ANOMEN] I... I am not sure I follow...~
@330  = ~[ARAN] No, Anomen, you don't follow, you lead! You can be th' glorious leader, an' show those nobles what for! Show 'em th' common man can trash th' effete pansies what keep 'em poor an' destitute in an imbalanced caste system! Long Live th' Revolution!~
@331  = ~[ANOMEN] By Torm, I believe the man has gone mad.~
@332  = ~[ARAN] Damned straight, by Sune's Rambunctious Rump. That be *my* job!~
@333  = ~[ARAN] Aye, that be th' truth. Except for th' stomach sickenin'. I probably put a might too much in th' way o' spices in last nights dinner, eh?~
@334  = ~[ARAN] That was a mite bit harsh. I blaspheme every day, an' naught bad happens.~
@335  = ~[ANOMEN] Your penalty will come, Aran. It will come, surely.~
@336  = ~[ARAN] Who be 'Shirley', an' is she right pretty?~
@337  = ~[ARAN] Nice language wi' th ' ladies, there, Delryn. Where be your precious 'chivalry', eh?~
@338  = ~[ANOMEN] Such creatures as that are not ladies, Whitehand. Though you certainly appear not to know the difference.~
@339  = ~[ARAN] Do you be talkin' to him, or me?~
@340  = ~[ANOMEN] Both.~
@341  = ~[ARAN] You have patience?~
@342  = ~[ANOMEN] You still stand. That should tell you that I have both patience and respect for <CHARNAME>.~
@343  = ~[ARAN] Riiiight. Got it. Come talk to me sometime, an' we'll have a bit o' a spar, you an' me,  an' we'll see whether that tongue of yours has anythin' backin' it up other than a pile dung what you call brains.~
@344  = ~[ANOMEN] I will instruct you presently, sellsword. Perhaps when <CHARNAME> no longer needs your dubious 'services'.~
@345  = ~[ARAN] Torm's Left Testicle, there you go again, lad. What in th' nine hells is wrong wi' you? That there 'garrison' be flesh an' blood, not some toys o' yours to be pushed about. We have power, an' we can use it better'n the poor lads what might get ground up doin' these 'trivial duties'.~
@346  = ~[ANOMEN] I merely thought...~
@347  = ~[ARAN] Oh, stick it up your arse, you soddin' bastard. You think only o' 'honor', 'duty', an' your own image. I'm shut o' talkin' to you. Someday mayhap you will grow up.~
@348  = ~[ANOMEN] Keep a civil tongue, Whitehand, or I shall cut it out for you.~
@349  = ~[ARAN] Heh. Pot, kettle.~
@350  = ~[ANOMEN] Did you speak, Whitehand?~
@351  = ~[ARAN] No, naught. Just mutterin' to myself.~
@352  = ~[ANOMEN] I see.~
@353  = ~[ARAN] For once, Anomen be right.~
@354  = ~[ANOMEN] You agree with me? Are you ill, Whitehand?~
@355  = ~[ARAN] No. I doubt it will happen again. But I done lived my whole life wi' th' motto "Th' Only Good Drow be a Dead Drow". I have seen naught to contradict that position.~
@356  = ~[ARAN] Aye, pay no attention to th' ba... th' kind gentleman, m'girl. He only opens his mouth when he wants to be changin' feet.~
@357  = ~[PC] You could lay a rose at my feet, but you had better do it quickly. Aran seems to have his eye on me as well...~
@358  = ~[PC] Anomen, I can speak with you, if you wish. But even though you are not a knight, are you so un-chivalrous that you would draw me away from Aran, when you know I am committed to him?~
@359  = ~[PC] Why, sir knight. I had thought you more observant. Anything you need to say can be said in front of Aran.~
@360  = ~[PC] Anomen... Aran has already indicated his interest...~
@361  = ~[PC] Anomen, if you were not committed to Helm, we might be able to work something out. But your faith would destroy any relationships I might want to make. Aran would be more forgiving. And I intend to live life to the fullest.~
@362  = ~[PC] I will never choose to abandon our friendship. But my heart is already set on Aran, even if he is a bit rough around the edges. The heart is blind that way, sometimes.~
@363  = ~[ANOMEN] Indeed, I have seen the way his eyes devour you. My lady, I would gladly teach the cur his place among us, if you would let me be your Champion.~
@364  = ~[PC] Do you respect me so little that you would question my judgment? I have already chosen, and it is not you.~
@365  = ~[PC] I need no knight, Anomen, and I am afraid I have given Aran a good deal more than a token or favor. I am sorry, but I cannot return your affection. We should just be friends.~
@366  = ~[PC] I need no knight, Anomen, and I am afraid I have fallen for Aran. I am sorry, but I cannot return your affection. We should just be friends.~
@367  = ~[PC] You flatter me with your attentions, Anomen. But I love someone else. Could you not see this as a gesture of Courtly Love, and serve me chastely, loving from afar?~
@368  = ~[ANOMEN] The sellsword is not worthy of you. I would gladly serve you as Champion and Protector, sworn to your side. May I hope that you might change your mind?~
@369  = ~[ANOMEN] My heart breaks with this news. I... I love you, <CHARNAME>, and it afflicts me to see you in another man's arms. But I will serve in what way you will allow. It is better to bear the pain now then to fight a hopeless cause.~
@370  = ~[ARAN] Somehow, I think th' joinin' part will be simple enough. Resolvin' this without blood bein' spilled, though, that be a mite bit more ticklish.~
@371  = ~[ARAN] Helm's Fist, Mazzy, let me take care o' this bastard for you. No call you mussin' yor hair none for th' likes o' him.~
@372  = ~[MAZZY] I do not interfere in your business, Aran. I will not be denied. You, churlish oaf, answer me.~
@373  = ~[TRGYP02] Your loyalty is your friend, your foe; your death, your life... it will bring you great happiness and great pain. Your sword swings wide of its mark, but your worth lies in the swing not the connection. There is little you will accomplish alone, yet you have the path of greatness open before you.~
@374  = ~[MADAM] Greetings, my <LADYLORD>.  I am Madame Nin, and I am here to ensure you are pleasantly accompanied.  Are you interested in companionship, my <LADYLORD>?~
@375  = ~[ARAN] Now, if I didn't already have my eye on a certain someone, I might be a bit interested, an' that be th' truth. But I was actually hopin' you might have one o' those Calshite bathin' places around here. Any luck on that?~
@376  = ~[ARAN] No, I think I won't rightly need anyone to help in that direction. I saw a lass up th' street what looked more like my type. You know, young... beautiful... unattainable... th' usual ego-smashin' fun a lad likes to subject himself to, eh?~
@377  = ~[MADAM] I am sorry, my <LADYLORD>.  We do not have a large enough establishment to offer such delights.~
@378  = ~"There once was a scribe, so I'm told,
whose cooking was warm, humor old.
In combat a lion,
in bed not half tryin',
But never a word less than bold!"~
@379  = ~[ARAN] Helm's Heavy Hand, that lad knows more than be good for his health, eh? Mayhap listenin' at one too many keyholes.~
@380  = ~"There once was a scribe from a coster,
Made curry so spicy it accost' her.
In combat a lion,
A' courtin' hard tryin',
Maidens a' swoon at his auster."~
@381  = ~[ARAN] Helm's Hard Horn, that there be a damn fool idea. Mayhap we had better wander on, an' not get too involved. No sense stickin' our d... err... No sense gettin' in th' way o' two fools who can't settle things peaceable.~
@382  = ~[ARAN] Cyric's Blazing Bum. Now I have seen it all. A ghostly apparition lookin' for his teddy bear. What's next, a demi-lich missing his baby rattle?~
@383  = ~[WELLYN] (sob!) I want my bear.~
@384  = ~[ARAN] Aye, we are in for an adventure, for sure. Bards be trickier than illusionists. Mostly more entertainin', though.~
@385  = ~[RAELIS] Why, thank you, sweet boy. That sounds like a high compliment.~
@386  = ~[ARAN] Your call, o' course, <CHARNAME>. Sounds like a good thing to do. Then again, most bards could talk a dragon into givin' up a scale or two , an' sell it back to him.~
@387  = ~[RAELIS] Ah! Someone in the Company has been telling that old dragon-scale tale again...~
@388  = ~[ARAN] You are playin' a dangerous game, <CHARNAME>, pickin' up work here. There won't be a contract to scribe on this one, I think.~
@389  = ~[LINVALE] What a charming young man. What a quaint concept... a written contract for work outside of the traditional guild structure. It almost amuses me.~
@390  = ~[ARAN] I don't hold much by off th' books work wi' a Thieves' Guildmaster. But you are leader, <CHARNAME>. I'd be careful, is all. Most knives play both ends against the middle. And they play permanent-like.~
@391  = ~[LINVALE] <CHARNAME>, you simply must let this man visit more often. I am sure that we can find suitable accommodations for him.~
@392  = ~[ARAN] That was not part o' the agreement. I know there wasn't a contract scribed, but this stinks. Honor among thieves, my bloody arse.~
@393  = ~[LINVALE] I am sure a healer can help you with that condition. If you are quite finished playing lawyer, I shall continue.~
@394  = ~[ARAN] Gifts, eh? Looks like downpayment for a contract extension to me. Fighter's Guild wouldn't do this, nor Merchant's Guild.~
@395  = ~[LINVALE] Those guilds are slightly less... creative in their conduct, shall we say? Perhaps you would consider being silent. I could quote something about 'as the grave' , but we are all friends here.~
@396  = ~[ARAN] Teos' Breath. These bast... err, I mean I am glad to be leavin' this fine crew far behind. I've lost more coin on their dice then I want to admit. And all my gear smells worse than the bilgewater.~
@397  = ~[HAVAREAN] So sorry about that, friend Aran. We were a bit cramped for space, and since your gear already was less than pleasant smelling, I thought you really wouldn't mind. We stored it in the bilge.~
@398  = ~[ARAN] Thanks ever so much. I'll be cleaning it for a week.~
@399  = ~[HAVAREAN] Don't worry. A small bit of time on this island, and you will think of bilge as sweet perfume.~
@400  = ~[ARAN] If this be no joke, I'll split you open like a rotten melon, you Cyric-buggerin' bastard. A contract's a contract.~
@401  = ~[HAVAREAN] I had no contract directly with you, my friend. Besides, sometimes the gods send us things that simply cannot be avoided.~
@402  = ~[ARAN] Well, never thought I'd be hidin' behind this kind o' visage. Luckily, I make almost everything look good.~
@403  = ~[IMOEN] And yer modest, too.~
@404  = ~[VICONIA] Shar's Breath, the jalup should be whipped. Remember your place, male. Do not speak unless spoken to, or no amount of illusion will save us from detection.~
@405  = ~[ARAN] You have to admit, Viconia. I do look good even as a stinking drow. Come on, you know you want me.~
@406  = ~[ARAN] You have to admit, Viconia. I do look good even as a stinking drow. Pity I am all into <CHARNAME>, or you would be all over me in a flash.~
@407  = ~[VICONIA] Silence this male, <CHARNAME>. Or I shall have his kidneys served as breakfast.~
@408  = ~[ARAN] Poison or curse or disease, it's just not right. Fight in the open, or ambush, that's fair. But all that rotting away from hiding is just wrong.~
@409  = ~[YOSHIMO] A worthy adversary knows his options, Aran. Perhaps Jaheira is too powerful an adversary, and he seeks to regain balance.~
@410  = ~[ARAN] Cyric's Left Wrist, you would do this?~
@411  = ~[YOSHIMO] No. I may capture or detain, but there is never profit in such ventures. This smells of pointless vendetta. That calls for an assassin, not a bounty hunter.~
@412  = ~[ARAN] Is there a bloody difference?~
@413  = ~[YOSHIMO] Yes. You speak truly. 'Bloody' is the correct difference.~
@414  = ~[JAHEIRA] Yoshimo, Aran, if you are both finished sidetracking this conversation, could we  get back to the point...~
@415  = ~[JAHEIRA] There is no serving of anything save vendetta here. A slaver would of course use such tactics.~
@416  = ~[ARAN] Helm's Hard Horn, that there be truth in advertisin', eh? Where do they spawn all these bastards, is what I want to know. On account' o' I never, never want to go there.~
@417  = ~[FSDRAGON] Turn back now.~
@418  = ~[ARAN] Whatever Guild you belong to, I'd be havin' a talk wi' your representative, eh? You done got th' worst assignment I can think of, short o' cleanin' up ogre pens in a circus.~
@419  = ~[GHOST] Helm is Duty. I serve Helm.~
@420  = ~[ARAN] Mielikki's Mithral Mane, that slippery bastard has us walkin' into a trap?~
@421  = ~[GORAPP1] Yes.~
@422  = ~[ARAN] Bloody hells... what was that? Felt like someone just walked on my grave.~
@423  = ~[ARAN] Riiiiight. Now I know what you mean when you say I talk too blighted much, eh?~
@424  = ~[GORMAD1] Talk, talk, talk, talk, talk!~
@425  = ~[ARAN] Well, by my reckonin', about a tenday's walk from th' left armpit o' th' universe.~
@426  = ~[GORMAD1] What do you mean?~
@427  = ~[ARAN] Hey - I be almost famous!~
@428  = ~[GORODR1] Could you introduce me to <PRO-HIMHER>? I have pressing business with the Child of Bhaal.~
@429  = ~[ARAN] Hey, I be th' almost famous companion o' <CHARNAME>! Well, I guess it be better than 'you there - the disposable bedwarmer'.~
@430  = ~[ARAN] I done heard an officer once say that evil always wins, unless good be very, very careful.~
@431  = ~[GORODR1] The Vigilant One agrees with this assessment.~
@432  = ~[ARAN] Hey, Odren - stick it up your arse, an' twist.~
@433  = ~[GORODR1] May Helm grant you wisdom. Or may He at least grant us your silence.~
@434  = ~[ARAN] Th' Prince o'... hey, Odren, you ever think o' workin' for th' Zhents? I would swear that level o' manipulation smacked o' th' Black Tower.~
@435  = ~[ARAN] I done thought bein' undead might be a rough contract, what with all th' long downtime an' all. But with slippers, a pipe, a nice fire, an' mayhap a dog to fetch an' carry, it sounds pretty decent, eh? If you can get over th' whole bein' dead thing.~
@436  = ~[GORPRI1] It has its own rewards, that is true.~
@437  = ~[ARAN] ... eyes up front, not on th' curves - eyes up front, not on th' curves - ...~
@438  = ~[GORSUC01] We should definitely ask it.~
@439  = ~[BODHI] You follow in the hopes of retrieving something dear to you. I say that the farther that you continue, the more that you will lose.~
@440  = ~[KORGAN] Why do they always talk so much? Gimme an axe.~
@441  = ~[ARAN] Stick it up your Bane-Blasted, Shar-Kissed stinkhole of a Lolth-Pissed arse, you Xvim-Buggerin' piece o' undead crap.~
@442  = ~[BODHI] How interesting. A toy that squeaks! And with such emotion, too.~
@443  = ~[MINSC] Cover your ears, Boo. I do not understand everything Aran is saying, but you are too young to hear such language.~
@444  = ~[VICONIA] Kill this creature now, and show your power, <CHARNAME>. Both she and the sellsword waste too much of our time.~
@445  = ~[BODHI] Consider your little pet sellsword, Aran. Wouldn't it be... unfortunate...  if something happened to one of you?~
@446  = ~[ARAN] Now, look what we be seein' here. A sentimental bloodsucker. There's naught you can do to <CHARNAME>. An' I done told you exactly what I think o' you.~
@447  = ~[BODHI] But I wonder, does <CHARNAME> fear your loss? Follow me further and you will lose more than you can imagine. That is a promise, not a threat.~
@448  = ~The Final Battle with Bodhi.

Bodhi appeared in an ambush shortly before I reached her haven, warning me that she was aware of my pursuit and stealing Aran from my side. Before she vanished and unleashed more of her undead creations upon me, Bodhi warned that if I continue I will lose even more than I thought possible. I cannot give up on the Rhynn Lanthorn... but now the life and immortal soul of Aran is at stake, as well!~
@449  = ~[PC] You have taken too much already! You will return both Imoen's soul and Aran!~
@450  = ~[PC] And you have delivered on that promise. Return Aran and perhaps I will be merciful.~
@451  = ~[PC] I would have hunted you for your theft of Aran alone. He is very important to me.~
@452  = ~[PC] You place too much confidence in sentiment. The theft of Aran will not save you.~
@453  = ~[PC] Well, we could have come to a simple agreement. But now you have been playing with too many of my toys, and I shall simply have to spank you.~
@454  = ~[PC] Have you noticed that so far everyone who challenges me loses?~
@455  = ~[BODHI] He is lost to you, <CHARNAME>. Aran was quite unreceptive to my discipline at first, but in the end he came along like a good little soldier. You could not have been that fond of him after all. All his resistance fell away with a bite and a gaze. Isn't that right, my little pet?~
@456  = ~The Final Battle with Bodhi.

Bodhi has turned Aran into a vampire!  Or... or very nearly.  The process may not have been completed in the short time Bodhi has had him.  Hopefully something can be done or I will have lost him.  Perhaps the elven war sage might know some way of restoration... or Elhan...~
@457  = ~[BODHI] An interesting ploy, though I am sure his fate will still serve as an example, whether you wish him back or not.~
@458  = ~[BODHI] Now, dear, you should understand your proper role. Here I am the adult, and you the child.~
@459  = ~[ARAN] Aye, mistress.~
@460  = ~[C6BODHI] Don't you see, <CHARNAME>? He is not even fully turned and he has betrayed you. Such a pretty little broken toy. A shame, after all he has done for you.~
@461  = ~[PC] Elhan! I've the half-vampire body of Aran here because of you! You'll tell me now!~
@462  = ~[PC] A friend is afflicted by vampirism.  An old book suggested that followers of Oghma might know something about that.~
@463  = ~[PC] I'm looking for information about a tome that details the curing of Vampirism.~
@464  = ~[MONK] Have you come seeking wisdom from the Binder of What is Known? The Wise God stands ready.~
@465  = ~[PC] No, thank you, I have no need of help at the moment.~
@466  = ~[PC] I need your help. Do you know anything about vampirism? An old book hinted that you might.~
@467  = ~[PC] I lost a companion in a battle with his sister, Bodhi.  I seek a means of curing him.~
@468  = ~[PC] A companion was taken by a vampire. What can I expect when I find them?~
@469  = ~[PC] Someone I care about has fallen to a vampire. Is there any way to save them?~
@470  = ~[DMTOWN1] By Helm... yer outfitted for battle. I'd give my right arm for some o' that gear.~
@471  = ~[DMTOWN2] Aye, now... you looks like a sword for hire, you does. You lookin' for some work?~
@472  = ~[GMTOWN01] Is that spitting really necessary? This is not the slums, you know.~
@473  = ~[GMTOWN01] Mmm...I haven't been to one of the spa tubs in ages.  It's the only luxury we, here, in the city really have.~
@474  = ~[GMTOWN02] You, there!  You look like the fighting type!  Are you in the army?  Can I join through you?~
@475  = ~[GMTOWN02] I am here to join the glorious army of Amn!  There are victories to be had and both coin and women to earn!~
@476  = ~[JAHEIRA] They... We are on the side of Balance.~
@477  = ~[ARAN] I love you like an older sister, an' trust you right fine, Jaheira. But when you talk that way, I think I don't rightly know you at all.~
@478  = ~[JAHEIRA] Life is not a shallow lake you wade into and paddle around in. There are forces that work to unbalance evertything, and Harpers work to keep those changes from hurting as many people as possible.~
@479  = ~[ARAN] Well, you keep your counsel, an' I'll be keepin' mine. If you was to take a stand about somethin' <CHARNAME> does, then fine. Have your say, an' be done wi' it, or move on. But settin' a whole organization onto judgin' th' acts o' one individual? Hells, what gives you th' right?~
@480  = ~[JAHEIRA] What gives you the right to act as you do? You sell your services to those who would pay your price, and you choose to accept service based on your own moral compass. You serve no higher truth than your own personal whim.~
@481  = ~[ARAN] Damned right, by Helm's Balls, I choose my own way. There be right an' wrong, an' no whinin' if you join up an' find out that you chose poorly. I have written some contracts what were just plain wrong, an' done some things what I be ashamed of. But *I* make th' choice on what be my path. I don't abrogate that responsibility to some shadowy group o' bastards I don't rghtly know.~
@482  = ~[JAHEIRA] No. It seems you hand it over to <CHARNAME>, and hide behind <PRO_HISHER> choices, rather than think for yourself.~
@483  = ~[PC] Enough. Both of you have valid points, but it really doesn't matter. Jaheira is welcome here, Harper or not.~
@484  = ~[PC] Should we set up a ticket booth? Sell some refreshments? Do you two need us to set up some sort of fighting circle or something?~
@485  = ~[PC] I was just tricked, duped, and used, and the first thing you two do is start fighting, instead of supporting me.~
@486  = ~[PC] There is an old saying; "keep your friends close and your enemies closer". I think that applies here.~
@487  = ~[PC] I trust both of you to do the right thing, even if you do it for different reasons.~
@488  = ~[PC] I have a great idea. Jaheira, stop being all "holier than thou"; it is unattractive. Aran, stop trying to make sense of things; you don't have the requisite wisdom.~
@489  = ~[RUMOR]Bromthar Helmbrind has been recruiting this season. He seems to be concentrating the role of the Red Shields on trade route protection, rather than regular battle readiness. If you can ride a horse, the Red Shields might be able to use your services.~
@490  = ~[RUMOR]Some idiot in Nashkel is trying to revive the Red Ravens. The darned fool must not know that Ryanna the Rose disbanded years and years ago. No decent sellsword would use that name, unless they were from Cormyr.~
@491  = ~[RUMOR]If you head down to Arrabar, I hear the Order of the Sapphire Crescent is hiring. For followers of Waukeen, they sure do skimp on coin, though.~
@492  = ~[RUMOR]The Blacktalons are always hiring, if you can stomach the work. They tend to play both sides of the fence, so you might guard a caravan one day, and raid it the next. They pay well, though.~
@493  = ~[RUMOR]I heard that a platoon of Soft Claws was accompanying a caravan through the city. It must be an important cargo, if the Neverwinter company is this far south.~
@494  = ~[RUMOR]A recruiter from Daggerdale was down from the Dale Lands last week, trying to get recruits. Teldra kicked him out, but he gave her the contract to raise a few recruits for an expedition to Teshendale. Not many are willing to get killed by the Zhents for so little coin, though.~
@495  = ~[RUMOR]If you really want to make coin with little risk of death, try the trading carracks here or at Waterdeep. Those ships are floating castles, and the pay is good.~
@496  = ~[RUMOR]The barmaid, Erika, has a new beau. Apparently, she has set her sights on the young apprentice blacksmith over at the wagonry. He blushes redder than his iron every time he sees her.~
@497  = ~[RUMOR]If you want steady work, you could always head to Tethyr. The Queen-Monarch is expanding the regular army. Not much adventure, but regular pay, three meals a day, a full set of equipment, and a good opportunity for advancement.~
@498  = ~[RUMOR]I hear that there are more mercenary companies hiring in Crimmor, because it is the starting point for so many expeditions headed north.~
@499  = ~[ANOMEN] Your language is offensive, Whitehand. You should think before speaking. Stubbing your toe like that does not warrant dispensing such calls to the gods.~
@500  = ~[ARAN] Bugger off, tin-can.~
@501  = ~[ANOMEN] I will not be treated with such disrespect. Your language offends me and is not appropriate for our company. Apologize at once, or I shall teach you your manners.~
@502  = ~[ARAN] Look, Delryn. How many wars have you served in? How many battles?~
@503  = ~[ANOMEN] That has no bearing on this discussion.~
@504  = ~[ARAN] If you ever sat down with your troops, laddie, you'd know that swearin' be a natural thing. And the tighter the spot, the tougher the language.~
@505  = ~[ANOMEN] There is no excuse for such offensive language in any situation.~
@506  = ~[ARAN] (sigh) Look, laddie. I'm not goin' to make a capital case o' this. I'm not one o' your troops. I'm not one o' your lords or such. An' I am not likely to curb my tongue. I served under an officer once who thought he'd clean us all up and make us gentleman.~
@507  = ~[ANOMEN] He obviously failed.~
@508  = ~[ARAN] To be fair, it was a mite bit difficult for him to try. We caught him in an Inn in Baldur's Gate, beat th' crap out of him, and tossed him bound an' gagged in the bilge o' a long-haul galley sailing for Calimport. By the time he got back, the Flaming Fist had decided he wasn't good combat material and made him a staff officer. Supply, I believe.~
@509  = ~[ARAN] Oghma's Truth, Delryn, don't you ever stop?~
@510  = ~[ANOMEN] Good hygiene is just as important on the trail as a clean and sharpened weapon, Whitehand. I comb through my hair as often as I polish my armor, for precisely the same reason. You could use some cleaning up yourself.~
@511  = ~[ARAN] What you call cleanin' I call preenin'.~
@512  = ~[ANOMEN] Our enemies should understand that they face a true and righteous foe, clean in mind, body, and spirit.~
@513  = ~[ARAN] By the Nine Brothers o' Hell, you have been on parade too long. Don't you know that all you're doing is settin' yourself up as a big shiny target, screaming 'kill me first, I'm too pretty to live'? For Torm's sake, at least put a cloak over that mirror polish.~
@514  = ~[ANOMEN] I do not expect you to understand.~
@515  = ~[ARAN] Ilmater's Blood, I do not expect you to survive.~
@516  = ~[AERIE] Why are you looking at me, Aran?~
@517  = ~[ARAN] Sorry. I meant no harm. I haven't seen many Avariel. I just was interested, is all. How you move, an' such.~
@518  = ~[AERIE] Y- you should not look at me that way, Aran. It reminds me of awful horrible times. To be gaped at and looked at like an exhibit. It is ugly, and mean.~
@519  = ~[ARAN] Kelemvor's Scales, Aerie, I didn't mean that at all. I... look. I have a bit o' a rovin' eye, and I appreciate th' female form. You are really beautiful. I didn't mean to offend. I was lookin' where I shouldn't, and I'll try not to look again. I just have not seen such a beautiful lass in a long time, beggin' your pardon.~
@520  = ~[AERIE] Me? I am not beautiful. You were... you were looking at things you shouldn't?~
@521  = ~[ARAN] Well, see, the hem o' your robe was slippin' a bit under the backpack strap, and there's a little bit o'...~
@522  = ~[AERIE] ARAN!~
@523  = ~[ARAN] See, me an' my big mouth. Now you've gone and covered up. And you blush bright, too. Sorry, didn't mean no harm.~
@524  = ~[AERIE] You could have warned me.~
@525  = ~[ARAN] I am sorry, Aerie. I'll try to be more gentlemanly next time. I promise, I really will.~
@526  = ~[ARAN] Aerie, do you want a hand practicin' a bit?~
@527  = ~[AERIE] Practicing?~
@528  = ~[ARAN] Practicin' combat moves. Sometimes magic isn't enough, you know. Sometimes you have to get a bit o' the rough an' tumble.~
@529  = ~[AERIE] Well, if you think it is a good idea...~
@530  = ~[ARAN] Sure. Here, hold this branch. No, girl, hold it like it was a dagger. Yes. Now, push it forward, and...~
@531  = ~[AERIE] EEEEK!~
@532  = ~[ARAN] See, that wraparound, an' you have your attacker pinned in your arms.~
@533  = ~[AERIE] Oh, I see. But Aran, your hands are... I mean, I wouldn't feel comfortable with my hands like that on someone I don't know.~
@534  = ~[ARAN] Oh. Sorry about that. Just a little high, I think. No, you'd want to be a bit lower. OK, you try.~
@535  = ~[AERIE] All right. So you lunge like this, and I twist like this, and swing, and...~
@536  = ~[ARAN] *urk*~
@537  = ~[AERIE] Oh, Aran, I am so sorry! I have a healing spell, I think; I didn't mean to hit so low! Can you straighten up at all?~
@538  = ~[ARAN] Nay, there, girl - you did right. Your attacker wouldn't be thinkin' much of anythin' for awhile. But let me alone just a bit, will you? Placing a healing touch down there is a mite more personal than I think you'd be wantin' between us.~
@539  = ~[CERND] At times you seem like the staunch oak of the northern hardwood forests, Aran. But you also appear as flexible as the willows growing by the soft midland rivers. Have you thought of serving the cause of balance and nature?~
@540  = ~[ARAN] You talk like a bard, my friend, not a druid.~
@541  = ~[CERND] Thank you. But you have not answered my question. Your skills and flexibility would serve the Great Balance well.~
@542  = ~[ARAN] Look, I appreciate th' compliment you intend, but Nature's a right harsh mistress.~
@543  = ~[CERND] You appear worthy of the challenge. You seem to swear by many gods, so I think you have no true calling. That risks your soul and your place on the Great Wheel.~
@544  = ~[ARAN] I think Tymora enjoys my takin' chances with the other gods. She guides my fortunes well enough. But I appreciate the compliment.~
@545  = ~[ARAN] Would you stop that?~
@546  = ~[CERND] Stop what, Aran?~
@547  = ~[ARAN] You be breakin' your stride, and hopping back an' forth. I can't watch for trouble with all that movin' about distractin' me.~
@548  = ~[CERND] I was merely avoiding the ants. Like small armies, they gather their food. They need no destruction to befall them from my stride through their habitat.~
@549  = ~[ARAN] You be playin' with me, aren't you.~
@550  = ~[CERND] No.~
@551  = ~[ARAN] Cyric's Flamin' Arse.~
@552  = ~[EDWIN] Hold this, sellsword. I must adjust my pack. You are not intelligent enough to do it correctly.~
@553  = ~[ARAN] Hold it yourself, red wizard. I be naught in th' way o' no Gond-blighted mechanical servant for your pleasure. Lean against me, if you are havin' trouble keepin' balanced.~
@554  = ~[EDWIN] If you were my servant, I would have you bound and whipped for daring to speak to me. Stop wriggling, ape. I still need to tighten the bottom strap.~
@555  = ~[ARAN] Hold on, I be havin' an itch myself...~
@556  = ~[EDWIN] FOOL! Your idiotic gyrations have cast me into the mire! I will run hot lead in the marrow of your bones!~
@557  = ~[ARAN] Great. The laughter's not helpin' matters, Haer'Dalis. Lend a hand, eh?~
@558  = ~[HAERDALIS] Why, my eagle, should I give you my hand? Do I not need it myself? How should I draw a weapon or gesture grandly? Besides, our fair wizard looks quite put out...~
@559  = ~[ARAN] All right, keep your temper, spellslinger. I have a waterskin for cleanup right here... oops.~
@560  = ~[EDWIN] (pffttt.) Run, simian. Mere incompetence does not explain dropping me into the mire then pouring water over my head. Your death will be slow, and painful.~
@561  = ~[KORGAN] Damn yer foul hide, Whitehand, I've not laughed so much since I don't know when. Here's yer gold. Next time I'll watch me bettin' with you more careful.~
@562  = ~[ARAN] Shut the nine hells up, you sorry dwarven bastard - now I have naught in th' way o' places to hide!~
@563  = ~[ARAN] Hey, sorry, Edwin, it were an honest mistake. I'm just a stupid blighted sellsword!~
@564  = ~[ARAN] Five gold to stop your laughin', Korgan. You're makin' him madder!~
@565  = ~[ARAN] 'Shoulda known better than to listen to you, Imoen. Now he's all pissed, an' I'm in trouble.~
@566  = ~[ARAN] Aerie, darlin', stop the giggling, will you. He's mad enough to spit fire. It's my life you be playin' with...~
@567  = ~[ARAN] Someone grab somethin' to help dry him off, will you? I am gettin' out of range right quick.~
@568  = ~[ARAN] Hey, wizard. Why don't you just whip us up some magical transport, an' give us all a rest. My feet are killin' me.~
@569  = ~[EDWIN] (If that truly were the case, I would ally myself with your feet, you overgrown chimp.) I could create such a transport. But a more intelligent being would recognize it as a broadcasting of both our power and our position.~
@570  = ~[ARAN] Well, with the gear we've got, every magic user within a mile should be able to see us blazin' like a torch, shouldn't they?~
@571  = ~[EDWIN] Leave the arcane discussions to your betters. Or even beings with some semblance of intelligence. You come ill-equipped for such conversation.~
@572  = ~[ARAN] Just tryin' to better myself. I can read an' read, but when push comes to shove, there be times when I need guidance. Figured you bein' smart and all, you could help out a bit.~
@573  = ~[EDWIN] My intelligence is more than adequate to bring your feeble strivings progress. I will assist you first by sending you on a quest for the definitions of 'can not' and 'will not'.~
@574  = ~[ARAN] So you are saying that you can help, but you won't.~
@575  = ~[EDWIN] Congratulations, sellsword. You have graduated from mindless slug to birdbrain.~
@576  = ~[HAERDALIS] Come, my brown eagle. Let us pass the time, and tell stories of valor and of victory, of love lost and found. Anything but the tedium of the endless march.~
@577  = ~[ARAN] I'd trade fair an' square with you, Haer'Dalis, but I've only got simple stories.~
@578  = ~[HAERDALIS] Ah, but the simplest are often the best. Come, tell me a tale. Entertain this poor sparrow, before he begins tearing at the nest in boredom and ennui!~
@579  = ~[ARAN] Well, I did hear tell of a bard who got bored one day. So he turns to his friend, and says, 'Fred, tell us a story.'~
@580  = ~[ARAN] So Fred, he gets up and he says, 'Well, I did hear tell of a bard who got bored one day. So he turns to his friend, and says, 'Fred, tell us a story.''~
@581  = ~[HAERDALIS] Aran.~
@582  = ~[HAERDALIS] ARAN.~
@583  = ~[ARAN] Yes, my friend?~
@584  = ~[HAERDALIS] I do believe that I understand the story. Perhaps we should explore song, instead, my eagle.~
@585  = ~[ARAN] Sure thing! Many's the time th' trail has been lightened by simple song. How about 'Ninety-nine bottles o' Ale on th' Wall, Ninety-nine bottles o' Ale, Take one down an' pass it around; Ninety-eight bottles o' Ale on the Wall. Ninety-eight bottles o' Ale on the Wall, Ninety-eight bottles o' Ale, Take one down...~
@586  = ~[HAERDALIS] May the gods have mercy on our ears.~
@587  = ~[ARAN] Hey, bard, my boyo... lend me a hand, will you?~
@588  = ~[HAERDALIS] I revel in the change and cadence of your speech, my eagle. You blend the accents of a dozen cultures in one sentence. What is it you wish?~
@589  = ~[ARAN] I can read this stuff here, but I can't remember it. I keep trying, but I just can't get it memorized. You seem to remember everything, an' your lifespan's a mite longer than mine. How do you do it?~
@590  = ~[HAERDALIS] Mnemonics. The occult study of memorization by association. For instance, I think of Artless Aran. That brings a mental picture of you, and assists my recall of all sorts of interesting things. Here, by fledgling, try it yourself. Look at a person, and think of a description mirroring the name. It will serve you well.~
@591  = ~[ARAN] OK, let me give it a shot. How about 'Happy Haer'Dalis'?~
@592  = ~[HAERDALIS] While this poor sparrow is not always happy, I think you have the idea, Aran. A huge generalization that acts as an index to memory. But keep your voice low, my friend. Not everyone is amused by playing such games with their names.~
@593  = ~[ARAN] Jabbing Jaheira. Pokes everyone all day with those elbows an' that tongue. Means well enough, though.~
@594  = ~[ARAN] Angelic Aerie. Beautiful, needs protection, damaged... but she'll take your heart with her eyes while you run from her constant complainin'.~
@595  = ~[ARAN] Jawin' Jan. He never shuts his trap. Nice, but just can't stop jawin'.~
@596  = ~[ARAN] Knightly Keldorn. OK, that is fair enough.~
@597  = ~[ARAN] Killer Korgan. Aye, that works.~
@598  = ~[ARAN] Merciful Mazzy. She is a stout heart, an' true.~
@599  = ~[ARAN] Mad Minsc. That's not quite right, though. Make it Magnificent. I'd take him 'side me on a shield wall any day o' the week, 'giant space hamster' an' all.~
@600  = ~[ARAN] Neophyte Nalia. It's a book word, but 'spoiled and clueless with a body to make a man blush' doesn't fit the pattern, I guess.~
@601  = ~[ARAN] Vehement Valygar. All business an' no real pleasure. Someone's got to get that man a pint an' a good tumble wi' a fine wench, and soon. Too tightly wound, that one.~
@602  = ~[ARAN] Arseholic Anomen. Stuck up prig.~
@603  = ~[ARAN] Vicious Viconia. Brings new meanin' to the phrase 'the only good drow is a dead drow'. Pity she's so useful. More pity I can't help her find her god. Preferably in small pieces ready for reassembly.~
@604  = ~[ARAN] Yoshimo. Hmmm. There's a challenge. How about Useful Yoshimo?~
@605  = ~[HAERDALIS] Not quite the letter of the game, all puns intended, but certainly within the spirit. Go on...~
@606  = ~[ARAN] Irrepressible Imoen. She gets dragged around, tortured, near to killed, an' she bounces back up an' keeps moving. There's a real woman, an' a fine companion.~
@607  = ~[ARAN] Adventurous Angelo. Good enough; he's seen a mite bit o' adventure on both sides o' this conflict, I think.~
@608  = ~[ARAN] Attractive Anishai. Sune's Slender Wrists, that one will drive a man to drink, she will.~
@609  = ~[ARAN] Aloof Azure. Not quite right, but close enough, on account o' her built in chaperon. Sharo's got one eye on me most o' th' time.~
@610  = ~[ARAN] Gallant Gavin. I'd have gone for Gregarious, on account o' he gets along wi' most folks, but he's a plain spoken lad, he is.~
@611  = ~[ARAN] Haldamir. Now, then, whet rhymes wi' 'H' what means 'keeps to himself at all times'? I done got it - I'll use an elven word for an elf. Helkaer Haldamir. Means 'icy one' in lammen Tel Quessir, that does.~
@612  = ~[ARAN] Bright Bouncin' Biddlekorak, on account o' he be followin' Lathander, an' he be short an' round like one o' them bouncin' ball children's toys.~
@613  = ~[ARAN] Bemused Britt. O' course, if you be readin' this line, you done CLUAConsoled a character what's not supposed to be in-party, and JCompton will be comin' around right smart to kick your sorry arse, he will.~
@614  = ~[ARAN] Twiggy Touchstone. That reminds me. I need to get th' boy a bath, an' right quick. There's bein' part o' nature, sure, but once in awhile it might be a good idea to wash some o' it off.~
@615  = ~[ARAN] Crazed Callisto. You don't rightly want to be around when she gets enraged, eh? There's no tellin' where her weapons get pointed.~
@616  = ~[ARAN] Chaotic Chloe. I'm not sayin' no more.~
@617  = ~[ARAN] Affable Alora. Tymora's Smile, that halflin' lass is th' sprightliest an' happiest bein' I know!~
@618  = ~[ARAN] Malevolent Miriam. Damned bloodsucker. I need to get me a now holy symbol an' some more garlic.~
@619  = ~[ARAN] Nimble Nikitalleria. Lathander's Light, what that girl can do wi' her fingers...~
@620  = ~[ARAN] Naughty Ninafer. Well, she's not, really, but a lad can hope for change, can't he? Pity she looks right through me, as if I'm not there.~
@621  = ~[ARAN] Cunning Coran. The boy's got charm, an' he's sharp, he is. But not much else goin' on, I think.~
@622  = ~[ARAN] Senseless SilverStar. I would run wi' 'sychotic', but it's not rightly spelled that way, now, eh?~
@623  = ~[ARAN] Amoral Alassa. Now I know amoral an' evil aren't rightly th' same thing, but it be close enough for me.~
@624  = ~[ARAN] Beautiful Branwen. That Tempus-lovin' girl be a sight for sore eyes, she is.~
@625  = ~[ARAN] Delicate Dynaheir. I don't rightly know no 'd' words for aristocratic, an' she's not dainty. In fact, she's not rightly delicate. Let's change that, eh? Make it Determined Dynaheir.~
@626  = ~[ARAN] Forceful Fade. She be th' kind what sees what she wants, an' gets it.~
@627  = ~[ARAN] Artless Andrei. It don't rightly fit completely, on account o' him bein' a smart lad, just a raw recruit. A bit sheltered. But close enough.~
@628  = ~[ARAN] Slippery Sebastian. I 'm not rightly sure I have gotten a straight answer out o' that one. Nine times out o' ten, I think he knows more than he lets on, eh?~
@629  = ~[ARAN] Insane Irenicus. Bloody mad, an' evil. But I guess <CHARNAME> can handle him.~
@630  = ~[ARAN] Good-natured Ghareth. He tells some nice stories, he does. Good lad.~
@631  = ~[ARAN] Chatty Cassius. Mask's Left Hand, the skald never shuts up, eh? Hey, don't be lookin' at me like that, Haer'Dalis! I shut up. Occasionally. When th' wind is right.~
@632  = ~[ARAN] Goey Gozaloth. That floatin' eyeball never did say what all that goo was. And I'm not rightly sure I wan to know, anyways.~
@633  = ~[ARAN] Harrowing Horace. I still get th' shakes just lookin' at him reachin for a weapon, straight through his own bony ribcage.~
@634  = ~[ARAN] Hungry Hubelpot. Corellon's Blade, he knows his food, he does. It's a right fine pleasure to watch him cook!~
@635  = ~[ARAN] Insolent Iylos. I suppose that be his job. But th' backtalk, well, he could be a mite more respectful. <CHARNAME>'s been a force for a long time, an' here comes th' big bad investigator.~
@636  = ~[ARAN] Kindred Kelsey. He knows merchant, he knows some fightin' ways - an' I do think he's a right fine party member.~
@637  = ~[ARAN] Barroom Bruce. On account o' I keep havin' to drag his sorry arse past, around, or out o' every single one we venture on.~
@638  = ~[ARAN] Arresting Auren. You look her direction, an' your eyes get stopped in their tracks, they do. In a good way, o' course.~
@639  = ~[ARAN] Shy Sarah, lass-o-me-heart. She is a right fine friend, she is. No extra garbage, quiet, straight to the point, an' a might shy.~
@640  = ~[ARAN] Scary Sheena. I keep expectin' to wake up as th' main course for her when she goes all firedrake random-like.~
@641  = ~[ARAN] Keen Kachiko. Keen mind, keen sword, keen tongue. Best to keep out o' all three's way.~
@642  = ~[ARAN] Kind Kari. Nice enough furrball, an' she's developin' some skills. Still scared o' her own shadow, though.~
@643  = ~[ARAN] Charismatic Keto. I know that's cheatin', but hey, it be my game - an' that lass is a right fine storyteller. She can drink me under th' table, sing like an angel, an' she's as smart as a whip. What's not to love?~
@644  = ~[ARAN] Kissable Kiara. Not that IO tried, or anythin'. I suspect she can kill me wi' her little finger. Them monks know things, they do.~
@645  = ~[ARAN] Killer Kindrek. Bloody evil Cyric Buggerin' Bastard. Gotta keep both eyes open while I sleep, I do.~
@646  = ~[ARAN] Kind Kiyone. She's nice enough, in her own way.~
@647  = ~[ARAN] Keep - An - Eye - On Kova. Hard to trust him, no matter what we find out.~
@648  = ~[ARAN] Auric Amber. She's cost a pretty coin or two to get sprung, but she does th' job an' brings in more coin to th' coffers, too.~
@649  = ~[ARAN] Smashin' Shy. Literally. Chende don't rightly know th' word 'subtle'.~
@650  = ~[ARAN] Artful Ariena. She'd make a right fine picture, she would. We would have to negotiate on how many clothes to leave on while posin', eh?~
@651  = ~[ARAN] Killer Kido. Bloody evil Cyric Lovin' naysayer.~
@652  = ~[ARAN] Friendly 'Fletcher. Good lad. An' it be a mite easier to find 'f' words what rhyme.~
@653  = ~[ARAN] Naughty Ninde. Or Necrophiliac Ninde; but for a spook-lover, she's right lively. I do enjoy watchin' her... err... back?~
@654  = ~[ARAN] Troublesome Tiax. Terrible Tiax's Troubles Tried Tempers Twice Today, Together T'will Tip Tiax' Top Toward Total Torture. There, I got me a blighted tongue twister.~
@655  = ~[ARAN] Xenophobic Xan, on account o' him bein' a Moonblade wielder an' all? No, it don't rightly fit. What's another 'X' word. Xysterous, like them healer's tools? No. Ok, how about wigglin' th' rules, an' goin' wi' Zealous Xan? He talks all doom an' gloom, but he doesn't back off from no fights.~
@656  = ~[ARAN] Dutiful Deheriana. She stayed true to Kivan right past th' changes on th' great wheel. But that was love, not duty. How about Deep, on account o' her deep love? Have to keep on thinkin' on that one.~
@657  = ~[ARAN] Keen-Eyed Kivan. He can put an arrow on target when I can't rightly see th' target, or th' horse th' target's ridin' or even th' stretch o' road th' target's movin' along.~
@658  = ~[ARAN] Animal Allison, on account o' her love for all them furry little creatures. An' the not so furry ones, too.~
@659  = ~[ARAN] Kiirar Kitanya's right out, o' course, as I am th' Chronicler, so to speak. Let's find another elven word what describes her. How about Koron en' naur Kitanya? She's a fireball, all right.~
@660  = ~[ARAN] Ravaging Rylorn. He'd love to see all Toril run wi' blood.~
@661  = ~[ARAN] Sexy Saerileth's not right on a couple o' levels, an' I don't want to offend no one. So how about Serious Saerileth? She is solid fixed on her purpose, she is.~
@662  = ~[ARAN] Youthful Yikari. She moves like th' wind in th' trees, an' she has that great accent.~
@663  = ~[ARAN] Silent Sime. She makes little enough sound when she's after a mark, eh?~
@664  = ~[ARAN] Knowledgeable Neh'Taniel. Yeah, I am cheatin', I am. But th' man talks deep, an' on a bunch o' subjects. It's like goin' back to tutorin' all over again.~
@665  = ~[ARAN] Sorrowful Solaufein. He don't rightly smile so much. O' course, I'd not trust him if he did, so I guess that is fine by me.~
@666  = ~[ARAN] Handy Hessa. Shes a right good advance scout.~
@667  = ~[ARAN] Lucky Linton. That woman can win a game o' cards, drink a keg o' ale, an' hold her own in th' brawl what results. Hardly ever loses, too.~
@668  = ~[ARAN] Thoughtful Tashia. She has great riddles, she does.~
@669  = ~[ARAN] Tremblin' Tsujatha. Only he don't. I don't rightly like th' necromantic bastard, but he don't back down. I'll have to think on him, eh?~
@670  = ~[ARAN] Vivisecting Valen. I suppose it don't rightly be vivisection when she sucks all their blood out an' chunks up th' still-twitchin' corpse, but that be close enough for me.~
@671  = ~[ARAN] Jumpin' Jonathan, on account he just hops right into battle wi' out sayin naught.~
@672  = ~[ARAN] Xenophobic Xulaye. Blighted drow bitch would kill us all if we weren't o' use to her.~
@673  = ~[ARAN] Yasraena. Nothin'. I got naught. I'll have to come back to her another day, eh~
@674  = ~[ARAN] Zaiya. You gotta be jokin', right? This one's a mite harder than most. Zany don't quite do th' job. Nope, I got nothin'. Wait a second... Zealous Zaiya. I think I might be gettin' the hang o' this.~
@675  = ~[ARAN] Now then, miss foxy lass, Moddy. How about Munchin' Moddie, on account o' her love for nice things what's to eat. No, I think it might be Vivacious Vixen, as she sure does keep close to her animal instincts.~
@676  = ~[ARAN] Able Ajantis. That don't catch th' whole honor an' knightly side o' things, but th' boy can swing a sword right fine, he can.~
@677  = ~[ARAN] Egregious Eldoth. Do that be a word, 'egregious'? I'd say 'slimy twisted bastard Eldoth', but it don't rightly rhyme, now, do it.~
@678  = ~[ARAN] Garrulous Garrick. That boy just don't rightly know when to shut up an' listen, eh? Why, Th' other day, we were just tryin' to get a good set o words in, an'...~
@679  = ~[HAERDALIS] The falcon is circling far from the nest...~
@680  = ~[ARAN] Right, sorry - got a bit sidetracked, eh? Let's see...~
@681  = ~[ARAN] Coarse Kagain. Now, I know that be more alliteration than th' spellin' o' it, but it fits right fine, it does!~
@682  = ~[ARAN] Mumblin' Montaron. He goes about all over th' place speakin' to himself in hushed tones. At least, I hope it be that an' not a spell he be about to put on me, eh?~
@683  = ~[ARAN] Quayle. Mystra's Mantle, Haer'Dalis, you make things a bit hard for a lad, eh?~
@684  = ~[ARAN] Silvery Safana. She likes th' jewelry, she does, an' she can talk you out o' or into just about anythin', so that silvery goes for th' tongue, too.~
@685  = ~[ARAN] Stern Shar-Teel. Aye, that works. She don't so much stare, really, as smack you between th' eyes wi' a glare.~
@686  = ~[ARAN] Sweet Skie, on account o' she be a right fine lady, an' easy on th' eyes. Mayhap a bit high maintenance, but sometimes that be a turn on, eh?~
@687  = ~[ARAN] Xzar. Hmmm. Nope. Naught in th' way o' help there. Mayhap I can come up wi' somethin in another language, but I be stumped on him.~
@688  = ~[ARAN] Mayhap 'Yarn-spinnin' Yeslick', on account o' all those stories he be spinnin' out.~
@689  = ~[ARAN] Adventurous Arath, mayhap? It fits his wanderin' ways. I wish I had th' knowledge to tie in 'animal', on account o' his other wanderin' ways, or mayhap because he watches out for 'em.~
@690  = ~[ARAN] Adventurous Arath, mayhap? No, I done used that for Angelo. Mayhap we swap Arse-kickin' on Angelo's, an' keep this for Arath. It fits his wanderin' ways. I wish I had th' knowledge to tie in 'animal', on account o' his other wanderin' ways, or mayhap because he watches out for 'em.~
@691  = ~[HAERDALIS] This is more entertaining than I thought it might be.~
@692  = ~[ARAN] <CHARNAME>. Hmmm. Not so sure I can guide on <PRO_HIMHER> so easily.~
@693  = ~[HAERDALIS] Ah, my fine friend, there are exceptions to every rule. You need not create a mnemonic for <CHARNAME>. In <PRO_HISHER> case, <PRO_HESHE> is quite unforgettable.~
@694  = ~[JAHEIRA] Aran. Come here. You have not secured your wineskin. Stop moving...~
@695  = ~[ARAN] Leave it alone, now. I'm appreciative an' all, but you are not my mother.~
@696  = ~[JAHEIRA] Nonsense. If you would stop charging about swatting at things before thinking, I would not have to treat you as a child.~
@697  = ~[ARAN] You don't look old enough to be my mother.~
@698  = ~[JAHEIRA] Nature demands age be shown in different manners to different races. That belt is too tight. Loosen it at once.~
@699  = ~[ARAN] You look way too shapely to be anyone's mother. In fact, your eyes, they OUCH!~
@700  = ~[JAHEIRA] Stop squirming. Flattery will not get you out of proper equipment discipline. And next time we pass a stream, avail yourself of Nature's bounty, and wash behind your ears.~
@701  = ~[ARAN] Tymora's Golden...~
@702  = ~[JAHEIRA] What did you say?~
@703  = ~[ARAN] Nothin'.~
@704  = ~[ARAN] Next time we cook, can you lend me a hand with th' spices?~
@705  = ~[JAHEIRA] I thought you kept your own stock from Calimport. No one has complained so far, at least in public. Why do you need my help?~
@706  = ~[ARAN] Well, my curries be fine, even given the strange ingredients we have to work with. An' my roasts are fine, too. But that last dish you cooked, it had good crunchy spiced things o' some sort, an' I want to learn how to make that.~
@707  = ~[JAHEIRA] Oh. The grubs.~
@708  = ~[ARAN] ...grubs...~
@709  = ~[JAHEIRA] Yes, yes... I am sure I have gone over this before, somewhere. Nutritious, simple, solid sources of nutrients, easily integrated into many recipes...~
@710  = ~[JAHEIRA] Aran?~
@711  = ~[JAHEIRA] No, please avoid being sick in that particular area. There are several important species living there that do not tolerate stomach acid well.~
@712  = ~[JAN] This reminds me of when my Great Uncle on my mother's side Maurice decided to...~
@713  = ~[ARAN] Jan, I didn't say anythin'.~
@714  = ~[JAN] I know. That was precisely why I thought of Great Uncle Maurice, who...~
@715  = ~[ARAN] I didn't say anythin', an' I didn't do anythin'.~
@716  = ~[JAN] Exactly. Maurice never did, either. It was years and years before anyone noticed it, and...~
@717  = ~[ARAN] I didn't say anythin', I didn't do anythin', an' you still are blatherin' on about a Shar-kissed family story. You don't take a hint, do you.~
@718  = ~[JAN] The same applied to Uncle Maurice, I am afraid. We finally found out he had died in the Great Turnip Blight of '72, during one of our famous Family Storytelling Competitions. He was just too bored to move on to the next part of the Great Wheel.~
@719  = ~[ARAN] I know just how he felt.~
@720  = ~[ARAN] Hey Jan, come here. take a look at this.~
@721  = ~[JAN] All I see is a small... oh. Now that is very cunning. A good snare, even if it is old, tripped, and exposed. It seems designed to capture small animals alive and unharmed, rather than the usual crippling or noose-like hunter's snare.~
@722  = ~[ARAN] Yes, but look here. There's a case made o' leather, with small loops inside that are still dry. Torn beyond repair now, but th' idea's sound. A vial for some kind of liquid, an' some loops for darts.~
@723  = ~[JAN] The snare is much more interesting. Quaint craftsmanship, but still a sound design.~
@724  = ~[ARAN] Do you think you could make me somethin' like this to hold my quills an' paper?~
@725  = ~[JAN] Oh, that would be child's play. I could do it in an hour. No special exploding traps, nothing but a simple watertight case.~
@726  = ~[ARAN] How much would it cost me?~
@727  = ~[JAN] Five nights of you cooking Turnip Curry.~
@728  = ~[ARAN] Two nights.~
@729  = ~[JAN] Four nights. With Turnip flatbread.~
@730  = ~[ARAN] Three nights, th' flatbread, an' I'll take your cleanup chores for th' week.~
@731  = ~[JAN] Done. Pleasure doing business with you.~
@732  = ~[ARAN] Likewise.~
@733  = ~[KELDORN] You have a gap on your right side.~
@734  = ~[ARAN] Pardon?~
@735  = ~[KELDORN] When you swing, you have an opening in your defenses on your right side.~
@736  = ~[ARAN] (sigh) I thought I'd fixed that. It's the lower right, exposin' the knee?~
@737  = ~[KELDORN] Yes. It is a common mistake for those trained as shield infantry. Flaming Fist?~
@738  = ~[ARAN] One campaign, Regulars. After three with th' Moonshae Axes, it were a bit o' a change. But there I wasn't on the wall. I got moved to subaltern.~
@739  = ~[KELDORN] The Iron Throne fiasco?~
@740  = ~[ARAN] Guilty as charged. Lots of men and women well past revivification when that mess were over. Battle of Cloakwood. Manticore's Point.~
@741  = ~[KELDORN] Ninety percent losses. You took both dragonstrike and a complete failure of gryphon support.~
@742  = ~[ARAN] Could have been worse. Could have been in th' Third Division. They saved our arses, at a terrible cost. Not enough scrolls o' Stone to Flesh in the whole bloody Sword Coast, an' then the Cyric-buggerin' Throne bastards started tossing boulders among the petrified, just out o' spite. Can't revivify someone who's been pulverized. Where were you?~
@743  = ~[KELDORN] Commanding the Third Division.~
@744  = ~[ARAN] Next inn, I am buyin'. An' you want me to do anythin', anythin' at all, my sword is yours.~
@745  = ~[ARAN] This work's a mite bit different from Merchant's Guild or even mercenary work. Very different from th' army.~
@746  = ~[KELDORN] It relies more on small unit tactics and magic use, but the fundamentals are the same.~
@747  = ~[ARAN] How so?~
@748  = ~[KELDORN] It requires close attention to your comrades, a carefully thought out plan, flexibility after contact with the enemy, and faith that we shall prevail.~
@749  = ~[ARAN] I just figure there be only so much we can do with so few against so many.~
@750  = ~[KELDORN] Aran, you forget. *We* are the few. That makes a tremendous difference.~
@751  = ~[KORGAN] Get out o' me way, ye great lunkin' arse. I can't see.~
@752  = ~[ARAN] There's naught to see, Korgan. No available females to leer at.~
@753  = ~[ARAN] Unless you count Jaheira's legs...~
@754  = ~[ARAN] Or are you lookin' at Mazzy again?~
@755  = ~[ARAN] Aerie complained to <CHARNAME> last time you tried to look up under her robes.~
@756  = ~[ARAN] Nalia is not your type, anyways.~
@757  = ~[ARAN] You can't be lookin' at the Drowess. Even you don't have that much a death wish.~
@758  = ~[ARAN] And if you are lookin' at Imoen, she's not lookin' so happy. I'd steer clear of her for awhile.~
@759  = ~[KORGAN] If you are all finished with yer blather, shaddup. Ye look down from th' top, I look up from th' bottom, an' neither gets naught but a glimpse o' flesh. Besides, better t' pay good coin fer a wench ye know will do th' job and then move on. No ties, no partners, an' ye get ter trade up when ye get more coin. Never th' same twice, if ye know what I be sayin'.~
@760  = ~[ARAN] Sounds lonelier than a half-orc trader in the Ten Towns. You don't want to feel like somethin' special, an' be the only one for her?~
@761  = ~[KORGAN] What, are ye deaf an' stupid, or just a woman? You been listenin' t' all that pansy elf-talk 'bout true love. All that mush slows a man down. I got places ter go, people ter kill, an' a fortune ter build. A weak woman will slow me down, an' a strong one will speed me up an' make me share th' profits. Damn 'em all, weak an' strong, ter the Ninth Ring o' Hades.~
@762  = ~[ARAN] Nope, I can't agree with that. I have enough trouble holdin' their attention when they be on *this* plane.~
@763  = ~[ARAN] Ho, shortaxe, you dropped somethin'.~
@764  = ~[KORGAN] Did not. Shut yer mouth, boyo.~
@765  = ~[ARAN] I be serious. Here. You dropped it.~
@766  = ~[KORGAN] Lemme see.~
@767  = ~[KORGAN] That's mine. You take it?~
@768  = ~[ARAN] Cyric's Blighted Arse, I just picked it up on account o' you dropped it.~
@769  = ~[KORGAN] What's your take?~
@770  = ~[ARAN] I don't want naught from you.~
@771  = ~[KORGAN] What's the catch?~
@772  = ~[ARAN] By Torm's Left Hand, no catch.~
@773  = ~[KORGAN] I'm a watchin' ye, boyo. Wi' both eyes.~
@774  = ~[ARAN] No good deed goes unpunished.~
@775  = ~[KORGAN] Shaddup. An' walk in front o' me.~
@776  = ~[MAZZY] Lift me up, please, Aran.~
@777  = ~[ARAN] Sure. What do you be needin'?~
@778  = ~[MAZZY] There are many advantages to being small. Unfortunately, getting a vantage point to see ahead is not one of them.~
@779  = ~[ARAN] I don't mind you ridin' on my shoulder for a bit.~
@780  = ~[MAZZY] No thank you. Just a quick look.~
@781  = ~[ARAN] Didn't mean to offend, or anythin'. You be no child, to protect. I'd lock shields with you on th' wall any day.~
@782  = ~[MAZZY] No offense taken. Lock shields? That doesn't seem like a good idea given our relative sizes. And I prefer my bow.~
@783  = ~[ARAN] No, sorry. It means I be right glad to watch your back, knowin' you will honorably watch mine.~
@784  = ~[MAZZY] Oh. Well then, thanks. Tell you what. You watch my head, I'll watch your ankles, and between the two of us we will square them off top and bottom.~
@785  = ~[ARAN] Sounds like a great plan.~
@786  = ~[ARAN] Mazzy, you pull a mean bow. You ever served in th' military?~
@787  = ~[MAZZY] We Hin do not really have a military to serve in, Aran. Just the TrueSwords. We defend when called.~
@788  = ~[ARAN] But I have seen mercenary companies of halfling folk. Some units of irregulars, slingers, mostly. An' I have heard of a whole company of your folk who ride mounted war pigs into battle, which sounds right funny. Except the man who told o' it spoke with respect, an' a whole orc tribal warparty confused, corralled, and massacred without loss.~
@789  = ~[MAZZY] We are an independent and self-reliant people. There are those who seek more adventure, and go beyond our communities. I have fought alongside companies similar to what you describe.~
@790  = ~[ARAN] Just not in 'em?~
@791  = ~[MAZZY] Aran, would it offend you if I said that being a sellsword is not particularly honorable among my people?~
@792  = ~[ARAN] No. 'Tis the same among many folks of many races. I'm no prize to bring home to mother, nor one to bring into polite company, even if I try not to swear too much. It doesn't offend me none.~
@793  = ~[MAZZY] Well, in my eyes, you are not a sellsword. You are a strong friend. I would be honored to bring you home to meet my family. On the understanding that you are a friend, of course.~
@794  = ~[MINSC] Look at this, Aran! Is this not a great weapon with which to smite evil?~
@795  = ~[ARAN] Aye, it be a right fine weapon. But I can tell you, th' weapon is not as important as th' wielder, Minsc.~
@796  = ~[MINSC] I do not understand. Do we not need weapons to buttkick for goodness?~
@797  = ~[ARAN] Well, I had a friend in the Moonshae Shield Company, see. She was a good fighter, out o' Ten Towns, followin' the ways of Tempus. We were in a tight spot, overrun, and the shield wall broke. Literally, in fact. That Gond-blighted crap they called 'iron' burst to shards in half o' our hands, so we had about half of us without weapons.~
@798  = ~[ARAN] Charis, she gets this funny look in her eye, just like you do sometimes, Minsc. An' she steps up in front o' the shield wall, and begins to chant. They charged us again, an' it looked dark, but Charis just grabbed hold o' one of the Throne lackeys. She took him an' used him as a huge mace, batterin' them down left, right, an' front, 'till there weren't much left of the charge, or of the Throne mercenaries either.~
@799  = ~[MINSC] This woman sounds like a valiant hero, Aran! I should like to meet her!~
@800  = ~[ARAN] I be in no hurry to make the introduction, my friend. Second campaign, she got caught by a wand o' paralysis, an' couldn't avoid a fire giant boulder hit. She's in Tempus' halls now, singin' and fightin'.~
@801  = ~[ARAN] Minsc, you are a good man. You protect Aerie right well.~
@802  = ~[MINSC] She is my witch.~
@803  = ~[ARAN] Well, look here, this be a mite bit delicate... but Aerie is a fine lookin' lass, and powerful. Haven't you ever thought, well...~
@804  = ~[MINSC] Boo helps me with thinking things, Aran, but even he cannot tell what you are asking. Thought what?~
@805  = ~[ARAN] She is a beautiful girl. You are a powerful man. She is dedicated to goodness. You are dedicated to goodness. She needs protection. You provide protection. Is any o' this makin' any sense?~
@806  = ~[MINSC] Of course, my friend. I do not need Boo to help me with this. She is my witch.~
@807  = ~[ARAN] (sigh) Minsc. Have you ever thought of askin' Aerie if she would be more than your witch?~
@808  = ~[MINSC] Aran, you are a funny man. What more could she be than my witch?~
@809  = ~[ARAN] Never you mind. But next time we are in town, I think you an' me, we are gonna go visit some public houses. Sounds like someone forgot to give you some basic education.~
@810  = ~[NALIA] Why are you avoiding me, Aran? I enjoy talking with people like you.~
@811  = ~[ARAN] People like me.~
@812  = ~[NALIA] Yes. I have helped many of your kind, and I try so hard to make sure that people of my class treat you people with respect.~
@813  = ~[ARAN] Look, Nalia. You are right good lookin', and I don't mind the chatter, but let's not talk about this any more.~
@814  = ~[NALIA] See, there you go again. Why are you avoiding me?~
@815  = ~[ARAN] Well, let's just say that I have had my fill of 'your people' using 'my people' as pawns in a live chess game. When battle starts, 'your people' are the ones in armor protected by magic, shielded an' away from the fray. 'My people' are the ones dying permanent-like, crushed and mangled by magic and siege engines.~
@816  = ~[NALIA] My father often said that is just the way the rules of war set things up, Aran.~
@817  = ~[ARAN] No offense to your father, Nalia, but there's the problem. In war, there are no rules, except one. Win.~
@818  = ~[ARAN] So, Nalia, you ever been dancin'?~
@819  = ~[NALIA] Of course. The Midwinter Festival, the regular series of social functions, and many lessons. I have even learned a few of your people's steps, those quaint country dances.~
@820  = ~[ARAN] Think you could teach me some steps next inn we stay at?~
@821  = ~[NALIA] That depends. Would you be trying to dance like you were at our last stay?~
@822  = ~[ARAN] She was right sprightly, wasn't she. I were thinkin'...~
@823  = ~[NALIA] I think we had better not, Aran. You two were spirited, but there are some things that a lady just doesn't do in public.~
@824  = ~[ARAN] Well, we could move into somewhere more private, you know.~
@825  = ~[NALIA] I don't know everything, Aran, but I think I can recognize a pass when I hear one. What would <CHARNAME> say?~
@826  = ~[ARAN] I was just jokin' wi' you, is all, Nalia. I wanted to see if you'd blush.~
@827  = ~[ARAN] I don't rightly know. Let's ask her.~
@828  = ~[NALIA] I'm not interested, Aran. You will have to find someone else to seduce.~
@829  = ~[VALYGAR] So, Whitehand, who are you?~
@830  = ~[ARAN] Let's just say... I'm a friend.~
@831  = ~[VALYGAR] That is not very enlightening.~
@832  = ~[ARAN] Look, did I say I were *your* friend?~
@833  = ~[VALYGAR] You did not. Perhaps I should rephrase my question. What do you do in this party, what is your purpose for existence, and why should I trust you with my life?~
@834  = ~[ARAN] I see things, an' I kill them. Once in awhile, they try to kill me.~
@835  = ~[VALYGAR] Ah. A kindred spirit.~
@836  = ~[ARAN] Why, do you kill things, too?~
@837  = ~[VALYGAR] Occasionally. Though lately, it appears that there are more things trying to kill me.~
@838  = ~[ARAN] Hey, the tryin', that's no problem. It only gets tricky if they manage to do it.~
@839  = ~[ARAN] Come on, Valygar, it's a great day, and we haven't been killed yet. There's probably a nice set o' monstrous creatures right over the next hill, waitin' to rip us into bloody chunks and serve us wi' a nice side dish, but right now, things are lookin' up!~
@840  = ~[VALYGAR] You just do not seem to understand, Aran. There will *always* be creatures bent on our destruction.~
@841  = ~[ARAN] Now that you mention it, we keep seein' more and more adversaries. We kill a few, an' then we move on, only to find more have taken their place.~
@842  = ~[VALYGAR] It is a vicious circle.~
@843  = ~[ARAN] Yep. Just keeps goin' around and around.~
@844  = ~[VALYGAR] It never stops.~
@845  = ~[ARAN] That's what makes it vicious.~
@846  = ~[VALYGAR] And a circle.~
@847  = ~[ARAN] You sure can depress a guy, boyo.~
@848  = ~[VICONIA] Stop staring at me, iblith. I have not summoned your attention to please me. Where I come from, there are consequences for males with eyes too bold.~
@849  = ~[ARAN] You flatter yourself, drowess. I'd as soon spawn wi' a spider.~
@850  = ~[VICONIA] Keep your eyes and your thoughts away, surface scum, or I shall make your meager existence painful.~
@851  = ~[ARAN] I'm no paladin of the Cryin' God, Drowess. I know what you represent, and what your kind do. You flinch once, an' I will be there, watchin' for my chance.~
@852  = ~[VICONIA] You are smarter than I thought, iblith. But your paranoia is wasted. Much greater forces than you have died waiting for that opportunity.~
@853  = ~[ARAN] Move away from me, Drowess.~
@854  = ~[VICONIA] I stand where I please, surfacer.~
@855  = ~[ARAN] Your stench gets on my nerves. An' I don't want you movin' behind me all the time in combat.~
@856  = ~[VICONIA] The only reason you remain alive, filth, is your meager utility as a meat-shield.~
@857  = ~[ARAN] Bad thinkin', Drowess. Now I know that, I might just stop, drop, an' roll next time the arrows head my way.~
@858  = ~[VICONIA] Your cowardice will be just as useful. While you are down there, you can lick my boots, as befits your station.~
@859  = ~[YOSHIMO] So, my fine friend. Do you think our leader knows exactly what <PRO_HESHE> is doing?~
@860  = ~[ARAN] Why are you askin', Yoshimo? You don't usually hold much wi' small talk.~
@861  = ~[YOSHIMO] I am interested in discovering the subtleties of common language. Your usage is most... interesting. I usually work alone. Perhaps you have an opinion I might find of use.~
@862  = ~[ARAN] Who knows, with <CHARNAME>? One day <PRO_HESHE>'s up, another day <PRO_HESHE>'s down. The <PRO_MANWOMAN>'s nuttier than a berrygobbler's cheeks in autumn. The point is... <PRO_HESHE>'s standin' right behind me, right?~
@863  = ~[YOSHIMO] Behind you, two feet to the left.~
@864  = ~[ARAN] Bugger.~
@865  = ~[ARAN] So, you hunt folks for fun an' profit, eh?~
@866  = ~[YOSHIMO] An interesting vocation, I know. And lucrative at times.~
@867  = ~[ARAN] I don't rightly know if I'd like that.~
@868  = ~[YOSHIMO] Friend Aran, when did the gods decree that we should enjoy our purposes in life?~
@869  = ~[ARAN] You've got a point there.~
@870  = ~[YOSHIMO] It is not as distasteful as it might seem. There are benefits to remaining on the open road, living the life of a hunter.~
@871  = ~[ARAN] What happens when it's time to stop an' retire?~
@872  = ~[YOSHIMO] There is planning, and then there is chancing the wrath of the gods. I will think of that when I am unable to lift myself from my bedroll.~
@873  = ~[IMOEN] Aran, you've gotta keep your eyes to yourself more.~
@874  = ~[ARAN] Hey, what did I do?~
@875  = ~[IMOEN] Well, you keep lettin' yer eyes drift south, so to speak. Every time you're talkin' to a girl.~
@876  = ~[ARAN] Cyric's black... oh, hells. Yep. I'm doin' it again, right?~
@877  = ~[IMOEN] Some girls might like that. But most don't want the unwanted attention, unless they're tellin' you they're interested.~
@878  = ~[ARAN] Are you tellin' me you be interested?~
@879  = ~[IMOEN] (*whack*)~
@880  = ~[ARAN] Ouch. Damn. Sorry. Not good to kid a friend what's tryin' to help out wi' the whole 'not tick women off' thing, eh?~
@881  = ~[IMOEN] Hey, no problem. That's what friends are for.~
@882  = ~[ARAN] Hey, Imoen, you OK?~
@883  = ~[IMOEN] I'm fine, Aran.~
@884  = ~[ARAN] You don't look fine. You look a mite sick, an' green about the gills. Plus, none o' your usual fire in the eyes. So, I gotta ask again... you OK?~
@885  = ~[IMOEN] Memories.~
@886  = ~[ARAN] Oh.~
@887  = ~[IMOEN] They don't go away, do they.~
@888  = ~[ARAN] Well, I've seen an' done some raw things in my time, for sure. An' there's times when the ones that hurt, you gotta go out an' bury them. Grab a willing lass for entertainment, get royally drunk, get thrown in jail, the whole rabble-rousin' carousin' crap.~
@889  = ~[IMOEN] Does that help?~
@890  = ~[ARAN] Hells, no. You wake up hung over, missin' your purse an' all your coin, an' no better off than when you left. But you forgot while it was happenin', see?~
@891  = ~[IMOEN] I don't think that will help me.~
@892  = ~[ARAN] Well, what if...~
@893  = ~[IMOEN] Aran, thanks, but quit trying to help. Some things a woman just has to learn to live through herself.~
@894  = ~[ARAN] Right enough. All I can say is, I wish there was somethin' I could do to help. Want to fix things, somehow, you know. Anyways, right. I'll be right over there, if I get needed or somethin'.~
@895  = ~[ARAN] You know, you looked a blighted sight better as a woman. Th' legs, in particular, was a right nice sight.~
@896  = ~[EDWIN] I will not have a lesser servant ogling my body, even in hindsight.~
@897  = ~[ARAN] Now, I didn't say nothin' about your rear end, not one word!~
@898  = ~[EDWIN] You dare to play word games with me, given your obvious lack of intellect?~
@899  = ~[ARAN] I guess th' whole sex-change curse didn't do anythin' for your personality. Once a bitch, always a bitch,eh?~
@900  = ~[EDWIN] Each insult is an extra torment for you, sellsword, when you finally leave <CHARNAME>'s shadow.~
@901  = ~[PC] Both of you, cut it out.~
@902  = ~[PC] Is there some reason why we are being forced to listen to you two bicker?~
@903  = ~[PC] Children, children... do you both need a time out?~
@904  = ~[PC] Aran, stop it.~
@905  = ~[PC] Edwin, shut up.~
@906  = ~[EDWIN] His heart, or his tongue?~
@907  = ~[EDWIN] At last. I would have been forced to turn that moronic baboon into offal. That would have been an insult to offal.~
@908  = ~[EDWIN] Do not test my patience by siding with this moronic baboon. I have had enough of his eyes undressing my superior physical form, and I do not wish to be the subject of his puerile dreams.~
@909  = ~[ARAN] Now, I don't rightly think that this be mine, eh?~ [c-aws045]
@910  = ~[PC] ARAN! Put that away before someone sees you!~
@911  = ~[PC] No, I think those are mine. Where did you find them?~
@912  = ~[PC] No, they are not mine. Do you want to explain why you have another woman's undergarment in your pack?~
@913  = ~[PC] I did not realize you liked women's clothes so much. We should put you in some of the 'armor' they make available to us, and see how you like having a chainmail bikini to hide your most intimate parts.~
@914  = ~[PC] ARAN! Put that away before someone sees you! Where in the nine hells did you come up with those?~
@915  = ~[PC] No, I think those are neither yours nor mine. Generally speaking, I do not wear women's underthings. Where did you find them?~
@916  = ~[PC] Do you want to explain why you have a woman's undergarment in your pack?~
@917  = ~[PC] I did not realize you liked women's clothes so much. We should put you in some of the 'armor' they make for them. On second thought, seeing you in a chainmail bikini is not something I would really like to experience.~
@918  = ~[ARAN] Since you be th' only female in this company, they must be yours.~
@919  = ~[PC] I think those are mine. Where did you find them?~
@920  = ~[PC] No, they are not mine. Do you want to explain why you have another woman's undergarment in your pack? Or perhaps how this occurred?~
@921  = ~[ARAN] Now, hold on a moment! There be only one time here... wait...~
@922  = ~[ARAN] Oh, Sune's Sweet Secrets. I done thought she were jokin'. If these are not yours, then they must o' come from that nice young lass at th' laundry. She seemed right interested, she did. I guess it might be some way o' catchin' my eye.~
@923  = ~[ARAN] Now, I should have figured they were naught in th' way o' your property, on account o' th' size.~
@924  = ~[PC] Why did I know you were going to make a comment like that?~
@925  = ~[PC] If that comment is about the size of my rear, you just signed your own death warrant.~
@926  = ~[PC] And how exactly would you know what size my undergarments are?~
@927  = ~[PC] I am not surprised you know exactly what would fit my figure. Your hands seem unable to stop re-mapping me.~
@928  = ~[PC] You of all people should know that it isn't the size that counts... it is what you can do with it.~
@929  = ~[PC] Are you sure she gave them to you, and you didn't take them so you could return them... perhaps some evening?~
@930  = ~[PC] Oh. I... Well. I guess some women might find you interesting.~
@931  = ~[PC] I think I have heard enough from you. Put those away, and get moving.~
@932  = ~[ARAN] I should have known they were naught o' your own by th' size alone, eh? I don't rightly think it be elven in make, neither.~
@933  = ~[ARAN] I should have known they were naught o' your own by th' size alone, eh? They might be a bit big... no, actually, they seem like th' right size after all.~
@934  = ~[PC] And how exactly would you know what size my undergarments should be?~
@935  = ~[ARAN] I should have known they were naught o' your own by th' size alone, eh? This be too narrow an' flimsy for a dwarven lass like you.~
@936  = ~[ARAN] I should have known they were naught o' your own by th' size alone, eh? Why, a Han lass like you could make this into a right fine slip, all on its own. Well, a pretty scanty slip, anyways.~
@937  = ~[ARAN] I should have known they were naught o' your own by th' size alone. This looks more like a half elf or human underthing, I imagine, not somethin' fit for a cute little gnomish lass like you. Though I guess you could make it work, eh?~
@938  = ~[ARAN] I should have known they were naught o' your own by th' size alone, eh? These would be a mite bit snug on you, at that.~
@939  = ~[ARAN] What I be tryin' to figure is why all th' fuss over a scrap o' linen. Although I suspect it has a mite to do wi' exactly what that scrap be coverin'. How about next time we do some clothes washin', you check where things be stored? People might get th' wrong idea.~
@940  = ~[ARAN] Mixed up in thy' socks an' such in my pack. Last time I did th' party chores, I must o' not sorted so well. Sorry about that. No harm done, eh?~
@941  = ~[PC] Those are some of my most private possessions! Give them to me right now.~
@942  = ~[PC] From now on, I will do my own washing. You stick to things that you are less likely to mess up.~
@943  = ~[PC] Well... I guess you could keep them...~
@944  = ~[ARAN] Well, Sune's Sweet Stomach, if they be not yours, then...~
@945  = ~[PC] ...probably <PLAYER2>'s... are you keeping them as some sort of souvenir?~
@946  = ~[PC] ...probably <PLAYER3>'s... are you keeping them as some sort of souvenir?~
@947  = ~[PC] ...probably <PLAYER4>'s... are you keeping them as some sort of souvenir?~
@948  = ~[PC] ...probably <PLAYER5>'s... are you keeping them as some sort of souvenir?~
@949  = ~[PC] ...probably <PLAYER6>'s... are you keeping them as some sort of souvenir?~
@950  = ~[ARAN] Just th' thought o' that hurts in places not mentionable in polite company, eh? But no, I don't find no excitement in these kinds o' clothin' unless th' owner be showin' em off to me with 'em on. You be sure they are not yours?~
@951  = ~[PC] Hey! Those are some of my most private possessions! Give them to me right now.~
@952  = ~[PC] They are mine. But... I guess you could keep them...~
@953  = ~[PC] Not mine, oh great washer of clothing. But by all means, keep holding a woman's private undergarments up and waving them about like a flag. It makes you look so masculine.~
@954  = ~[PC] I gave up on collecting women's underclothing back in Candlekeep. It never did appeal to me much, anyways. Now, peeking in on the baths, that was much more fun.~
@955  = ~[PC] Why collect women's undergarments when what they conceal is so much more interesting?~
@956  = ~[PC] Look, grow up. They are clothes. Just figure out who's they are, and get it sorted out. What are you, twelve?~
@957  = ~[ARAN] Hells, I know better ways o' attractin' th' attention o' th' opposite sex.~
@958  = ~[ARAN] Blighted hells, you are givin' me way too much information, boyo. Your particular matin' habits be none o' my concern, unless we both be after th' same game, eh? Unless you have a few juicy stories to pass th' time, that is.~
@959  = ~[ARAN] I... err... you...~
@960  = ~[ARAN] Oh, Grumbar's Hardened Hide, I just put both feet right in my mouth, an' now naught I say can tell you what I meant wi' out makin' you more insulted. I'm callin' this a loss, an' shuttin' th' hells up.~
@961  = ~[ARAN] Mayhap I had better be slippin' these into <PLAYER2>'s pack. An' next washday, I think I will have naught in th' way o' lettin' others do it, an' save myself th' possibilities o' her gettin' th' wrong idea.~
@962  = ~[ARAN] Mayhap I had better be slippin' these into <PLAYER3>'s pack. An' next washday, I think I will have naught in th' way o' lettin' others do it, an' save myself th' possibilities o' her gettin' th' wrong idea.~
@963  = ~[ARAN] Mayhap I had better be slippin' these into <PLAYER4>'s pack. An' next washday, I think I will have naught in th' way o' lettin' others do it, an' save myself th' possibilities o' her gettin' th' wrong idea.~
@964  = ~[ARAN] Mayhap I had better be slippin' these into <PLAYER5>'s pack. An' next washday, I think I will have naught in th' way o' lettin' others do it, an' save myself th' possibilities o' her gettin' th' wrong idea.~
@965  = ~[ARAN] Mayhap I had better be slippin' these into <PLAYER6>'s pack. An' next washday, I think I will have naught in th' way o' lettin' others do it, an' save myself th' possibilities o' her gettin' th' wrong idea.~
@966  = ~[ARAN] All that fuss over a little scrap o' clothin' no bigger than a good-sized handkerchief. But here you go. Don't want no one to think I be keepin' your panties as no souvenir or naught like that. Bad for morale, eh?~
@967  = ~[ARAN] Or worse, they might get the right idea.~
@968  = ~[ARAN] No why would I want to be doin' that? It seems a right strange thing to use as a token or favor, an' I be no knightly jouster. All that fuss over a little scrap o' clothin' no bigger than a good-sized handkerchief. Here you go. Otherwise, it might be bad for morale, eh?~
@969  = ~[ARAN] Now why would I want to be doin' that? Me, I'm a right simple soul. I'd much rather get rid o' such nonsense an' see you th' way th' gods created you. All that fuss over a little scrap o' clothin' no bigger than a good-sized handkerchief. Here you go. I'll be a mite more careful sortin' next laundry day.~
@970  = ~[ARAN] Bane's Blood, she be blushin' worse than a beet at fall harvest. She damned near glows! I guess I will not be volunteerin' to do no more o' th' group laundry anytime soon.~
@971  = ~[ARAN] Itishia's Icy Iris, that were one cold glance she just gave me. Gave me th' chills, it did. I guess I will not be volunteerin' to do no more o' th' group laundry anytime soon.~
@972  = ~[ARAN] Bane's Blood, I don't rightly know whose this be. But someone be missin' some right private clothin'. I guess I will not be volunteerin' to do no more o' th' group laundry anytime soon.~
@973  = ~[ARAN] Hey! Put that down! That don't rightly belong to you!~ [c-aws046]
@974  = ~[PC] This little scrap of paper? Here, I did not realize that it was yours.~
@975  = ~[PC] Anything left out in public is mine. Why? What is on it?~
@976  = ~[PC] A random scrap of parchment lying around has no owner. I think I shall read it aloud, though, since you seem so worried about me picking it up...~
@977  = ~[PC] You should keep a closer eye on your belongings. Your punishment for carelessness is that I shall read it aloud.~
@978  = ~[ARAN] Thank you right kindly. You didn't read it, now, did you?~
@979  = ~[PC] Unfortunately, yes. The imagery was quite... detailed. One might even say explicit.~
@980  = ~[PC] Not yet. But anything left out in public is mine. Why? What is on it?~
@981  = ~[PC] Of course not. Though if it is private, I think you should be more careful about how you dispose of things like this in the future.~
@982  = ~[ARAN] Nothin' much. Just some scrapped practice writin'. Nothin' there, no <PRO_SIRMAAM>, nothin' to see.~
@983  = ~[PC] Unfortunately, I just lied to you. I read it. The imagery was quite... graphic. One might even say explicit. And apparently, you are very creative in your approach to spelling.~
@984  = ~[ARAN] Come on, <CHARNAME>... be a good <PRO_MANWOMAN>, a credit to all what call themselves '<PRO_RACE>'. It were a rough draft, and a bad one at that. Just give me th' blasted thing an' forget you ever saw it, eh?~
@985  = ~[PC] "My Dearest Love, how can I count the ways that you excite me, how you arouse my innermost passions and lusts." Hey, Aran, you misspelled 'excite', unless Chondathan somehow borrowed several Rashemite alphabet characters while I was not paying attention. "The way that your..." not going to read that word... nor that one... "move, bouncing like twin horses tethered in tandem, two terrific trepidatious terrific..." No, you spelled that wrong, too... err... I have never heard that body part described quite that way. Hmmm. So, you are a leg man, too? No, you seem to go on and on about wondrous caves of passion, and something about spelunking, and here you have split an infinitive... 'to boldly go where no man has gone before?' Quite colorful. I think you should go into comedy writing with Volo.~
@986  = ~[PC] Of course I will give it to you. Though if it is private, I think you should be more careful about how you dispose of things like this in the future.~
@987  = ~[PC] Of course I will give it to you. Though I did get a glimpse at the salutation. 'My Dearest Love'? Who were you writing to?~
@988  = ~[ARAN] <CHARNAME>, for th' love o' th' gods, stop readin' that an' give it back, eh?~
@989  = ~[PC] Oh, no. I intend to keep this and read it at our next inn. It should be good for a laugh and a free round of drinks. You couldn't get a professional Bard to write some of this stuff!~
@990  = ~[PC] Only one question... who was this draft intended for? What gracious woman were you intending to reduce to a puddle of laughter with this missive of misplaced words and awkward imagery?~
@991  = ~[PC] I had no idea you were so colorful in your writing, Aran. I thought you might parse a love letter "If the party in the fore-said paragraph, to be henceforth referred to as 'The Lover', does agree to a private meeting the time of which is to consist of not less than one-half (1/2) hour, as determined by the established Dalereckoning Sundial, then aforesaid party shall indicate acceptance by..."~
@992  = ~[ARAN] Wild horses couldn't get that answer out o' me, no way, no how. Oh, Bane's Blood, go on then. Laugh away. I'll be on about my business.~
@993  = ~[ARAN] Banes Broken Bones. I should take to eatin' my trial versions just to make sure they don't fall into th' wrong hands.~
@994  = ~[ARAN] Hey, I never said my dreams be pure... wait... somehow, I don't think I understood th' objection.~
@995  = ~[ARAN] Well, he blighted well started it...~
@996  = ~[AERIE] ARAN! Th... those are mine.~
@997  = ~[NALIA] That is personal property, and finding quality silk and lacework around here is difficult. Give them to me, please.~
@998  = ~[EDWINA] You foul creature! Unhand my undergarments, you moronic baboon. And keep your lusts to yourself. I may be a magnificent looking woman, but I am still Edwin Odesseiron, Red Wizard. Indignities will be met with swift and horrific punishment!~
@999  = ~[JAHEIRA] Underclothing is functional protection provided for the comfort of the wearer. I will reclaim mine now, Aran.~
@1000 = ~[VICONIA] Spidersilk is expensive, rivvil. If a single strand is damaged, I shall carve temporary patches out of your skin.~
@1001 = ~[IMOEN] Hey! That's mine! Give 'em here!~
@1002 = ~[ARAN] Honest to th' gods, I didn't touch anythin', or bust anythin', or even look crossways at naught! None o' this be my doin'!~
@1003 = ~[ARAN] Look at all th' pretty colors. Real nice, eh?~ [c-aws047]
@1004 = ~[PC] Hey, Aran, repeat after me... "We must all think for ourselves"...~
@1005 = ~[PC] Drink this cup of mud. It will make you feel better.~
@1006 = ~[PC] Hey you have a fly on your nose. Swat it, quick!~
@1007 = ~[PC] You owe me money, boyo. Come on, 20 gold, right now.~
@1008 = ~[PC] Now I have you where I want you. Kiss my bottom, sellsword.~
@1009 = ~[PC] Go to sleep, Aran, and dream of large women.~
@1010 = ~[PC] Hey, Aran, stand on your head.~
@1011 = ~[PC] Hey, Aran, stick a dagger where the sun doesn't shine.~
@1012 = ~[PC] Are you all right? It looks like you have been charmed or something.~
@1013 = ~[PC] So, what do you really think of <PLAYER2>?~
@1014 = ~[PC] So, what do you really think of <PLAYER3>?~
@1015 = ~[PC] So, what do you really think of <PLAYER4>?~
@1016 = ~[PC] So, what do you really think of <PLAYER5>?~
@1017 = ~[PC] So, what do you really think of <PLAYER6>?~
@1018 = ~[PC] So, what do you really think of me?~
@1019 = ~[ARAN] Now, tha... that last round, it packed one hell o' a... hell o' a wallop. Hey, stop weavin' about so much, <CHARNAME>.~ [c-aws048]
@1020 = ~[PC] You seem to have had too much to drink. Perhaps we should get you to bed.~
@1021 = ~[PC] Oh, come on. You haven't had that much to drink. I bet I can drink you under the table.~
@1022 = ~[PC] Hey, keep your voice down. You are starting to attract attention.~
@1023 = ~[ARAN] Now, tha... that last round, it packed one hell o' a... hell o' a wallop. This room be spinnin' somethin' fierce.~ [c-aws049]
@1024 = ~[PC] Hey, didn't we already have this conversation?~
@1025 = ~[PC] I think the young redhead at the end of the bar is looking at you, Aran.~
@1026 = ~[ARAN] I kept my blighted mouth shut, on account o' I didn't trust myself to stay in my Cyric-lovin' place, an' not start more trouble. But I have had my fill o' slippery connivin' Harper tricks. Mayhap it be just me, but it seems we'd be a mite bit safer if we just stayed th' blighted hells away from anyone associatin' wi' th' Harpers. I thought they were on th' side o' good.~
@1027 = ~[ARAN] Jergal's Moldy Wrappings, that bastard could take a hit, he could. I guess th' whole 'live forever' thing didn't rightly work out for him, though. He should have remembered that sometimes th' gods are right bastards, an' grant you exactly what you think you want, eh?~ [c-aws050]
@1028 = ~[ARAN] Ah, light! Lathander's Luminated Lamp, that's a right fine thing to see. I was beginnin' to think we'd never see naught but shadow, darkness, an' death. Does a body good to see some sun shine down on this place.~ [c-aws051]
@1029 = ~[ARAN] Lathander's Bright Buttocks, it be right fine to see you alive an' well, Gavin m'lad. Though, I do have to say, you look like hell. Strike that... I seen a bit o' hell, an' you look worse.~ [c-aws070]
@1030 = ~[ARAN] Jergal's Moldy Wrappings, that stinks. Usually, I'm all for 'when in Calimport, act as a Calimshan'. But slavery's just wrong, no matter where an' when.~ [c-aws063]
@1031 = ~[ARAN] Well, now, that be right kind o' you to put me as leader. I'll take point if you want me to, but you still be callin' th' shots, eh? On account o' I don't rightly trust my own judgment at times. I'm likely to go pokin' my nose into somethin' you don't want to disturb.~ [c-aws064]
@1032 = ~[ARAN] Umberlee's Fickle Breath, you look tired, <CHARNAME>. We had better find some place t' rest a bit, eh? Some nice tea, a bit to eat, sleep... does a body good, you know.~ [c-aws065]
@1033 = ~[ARAN] Whoever done said 'if looks could kill' must not o' run into one o' those buggers, eh? I wonder what two o' them sparkin' must be like. 'Honey, do I look nice to you?' 'Why, yes, darlin' - oops. Well, so much for a first date. I wonder if she has a sister what's blind?'~ [c-aws053]
@1034 = ~[ARAN] An' here I thought I was shut o' those poison-spittin' etter-crappers. Cloakwood had its fair share o' them, plus some wyverns an' a spider or two, too. I think I prefer undead. At least they don't be all sticky. Well, mostly.~ [c-aws054]
@1035 = ~[ARAN] By Grumbar's Clay Fist, golems are a pain in the arse. But th' bigger they are, th' harder they fall, eh? Just as long as you are out o' th' way when it happens, things work out fine.~ [c-aws055]
@1036 = ~[ARAN] Beshaba's Breath, that last zombie done give me th' shivers. It was like lookin' in a mirror after a night playin' Fox an' Hounds across th' docks district in Neverwinter. Actually, that's not rightly fair. Th' zombie looked a mite better than I did.~ [c-aws056]
@1037 = ~[ARAN] Look, I be a decent sort o' sellsword, an' I don't question orders most times. In fact, I'm not rightly questionin' them now. All I be sayin' is, wi' an employer like her, we had best keep our eyes open day an' night. Most especially night.~ [c-aws057]
@1038 = ~[ARAN] Shadow Thieves. Bloodscalp. Linvale. You know, that's one serious kettle o' stew to jump in. Not that you can't handle it, <CHARNAME>... I just be thinkin' I need to start sleepin' in my armor, on account o' th' 'friends' we be gatherin'.~ [c-aws058]
@1039 = ~[ARAN] Bane's Bronzed Bones, I should have had less o' th' curry... oh. That be troll stench. Sorry, though it was dinner kickin' up a bit.~ [c-aws059]
@1040 = ~[ARAN] Bloodsuckers. Great. An' I don't mean th' normal kind, you know, what you meet in guildhalls an' government houses - these be th' ones what beat death an' taxes combined.~ [c-aws060]
@1041 = ~[ARAN] I'd be a mite happier if I could see what I'm supposed to be hittin'.~ [c-aws061]
@1042 = ~[ARAN] I don't believe it.~ [c-aws052]
@1043 = ~[ARAN] Well, now there be a sight you do not rightly see every day. A Drowess takin' an interest in a human what doesn't involve flayin' skin off o' said human.~ [c-aws062]
@1044 = ~[ARAN] Greetin's, oh Great an' Wise Oghma, Keeper of Lore an' Flame o' Knowledge - how's my girl doin' eh? Nice to see that there's still a ton o' things to read, an' visitin' the old girl's haunts is always a right fine experience. I'll be over here, browsin' through th' stacks.~ [c-aws066]
@1045 = ~[ARAN] Home o' th' Cryin' God, an' any poor soul what's washed up here. Not that I'm judgin', mind you. A follower or two o' his has pulled me out o' more than one tight spot, an' not always after a battle. I'd better make a donation.~ [c-aws067]
@1046 = ~[ARAN] Hey, someone kick me if I open my mouth in here, eh? Somehow, I don't rightly think th' Just One looks kindly on my playin' fast an' loose wi' his name.~ [c-aws068]
@1047 = ~[ARAN] Ah, bright an' shinin' glory for the Sun Lord, eh? You got to love a god what lets you turn over a new leaf every day. Speakin' o' which, excuse me a second - there be a right fine lookin' young Lathanderite over there, an' I think she's lookin' favorable at me.~ [c-aws069]
@1048 = ~[PC] Move one inch toward her, Aran, and I will have you thrown out of here on your ear.~
@1049 = ~[PC] Hey, put in a word for me with her redheaded friend, will you?~
@1050 = ~[PC] Do you ever think of anything but swearing, drinking, eating, sex, and fighting?~
@1051 = ~[PC] Can someone hit Aran for me? I am not able to reach him from here.~
@1052 = ~[ARAN] By th' Queen-Bi... err... mayhap I just shut my mouth. She might just decide to grant me an audience I'm not ready to have. Mayhap I should wait outside, or stuff somethin' in my mouth, or somethin'.~ [c-aws071]
@1053 = ~[ARAN] Now here's a goddess worth lookin' to. She be no Tymora, bless her Golden Coin, but between Tymora's Luck, Waukeen's Bounty, an' Ilmater's Mercy, there's naught a man can do but prosper, eh?~ [c-aws072]
@1054 = ~[ARAN] Tymora's Luck, let's blighted well not wake up whatever th' hells that be, eh? I want at least one piece o' my hide to be unscarred an' unbroken.~ [c-aws072]
@1055 = ~[ARAN] Well, now. I thought I had seen everythin' possible in th' way o' dragons. Never did see one what was like that. Wasn't even sure how to kill th' Cyric-blighted thing.~
@1056 = ~[PC] You really, really don't like dragons, do you.~
@1057 = ~[PC] So, you have seen lots of different dragons?~
@1058 = ~[PC] You are never sure of anything.~
@1059 = ~[PC] Let me guess. You had friends headed for Cormyr to deal with those dragons going rogue and terrorizing the countryside.~
@1060 = ~[PC] Oh, come on. That was not the worst we could have faced. I have heard stories of how the great ones fought their deaths: Aerihykloarara, Agoshyrvor, Agyrtclughwaur, Angkarasce...~
@1061 = ~[PC] You have to get over this dragon thing, Aran. It is really getting tiresome.~
@1062 = ~[ARAN] By the nine planes o' hell, that be one horrible old biddy. Th' Keep's been taken, and she be talkin' to the rescue party like that. Reminds me of my mother, only wi' out the charm and panache.~ [c-aws073]
@1063 = ~[ARAN] Clangedden's Beard. I don't know whether to laugh at that old bat, or send her up front in th' next battle to scare th' trolls. No wonder Nalia is so... err... shuttin' up now.~
@1064 = ~[PC] That would be a good idea, Aran. It saves me telling you to take your foot out of your mouth.~
@1065 = ~[PC] I agree, Aran. But that isn't quite the most diplomatic thing to say, is it?~
@1066 = ~[PC] If I wanted your opinion, I would have asked for it.~
@1067 = ~[PC] Do you have a problem with Nalia?~
@1068 = ~[PC] Hey, leave her alone. She has been through a horrible ordeal.~
@1069 = ~[ARAN] You know, I thought it might be right fine to pay respects to th' dead, an' wander among th' headstones. Thought it might be peaceful, an' not spooky at all.~
@1070 = ~[ARAN] Then again, mother always did say I were a proper idiot.~
@1071 = ~[ARAN] Somehow, it seems th' type o' folks you meet in a boneyard just don't always seem to have th' best interest o' me an' mine held proper. Mayhap we stop all this grave-grubbin', at least until after daylight. This place be a mite less than cheerful, eh?~
@1072 = ~[ARAN] Birds. Daylight. Sunrise. Blighted hells, it be nice to stretch out after a real sleep, an' see th' sky...~ [c-aws110]
@1073 = ~[ARAN] Stars. Breezes. Selune Herself, shinin' down. Blighted hells, it be nice to stretch out after a real sleep, an' see th' sky...~ [c-aws111]
@1074 = ~[ARAN] Do you think we could move this along a little? This place be my idea o' a nightmare wrapped up in one o' those tales told to scare children.~ [c-aws074]
@1075 = ~[PC] We are moving along as best we can. Calm down, take a big breath, and get yourself under control. The Underdark may be legendary, but then again, so are we.~
@1076 = ~[PC] Oh, shut up. What a big baby. You talk about being a tough military man, yet go all weak-kneed at a little fungus and some Drow?~
@1077 = ~[PC] It is bothering me, too, Aran. But complaining about it will not get us any further.~
@1078 = ~[PC] It is not a great time to talk right now, Aran. If you want this over with quickly, stop wasting time with smalltalk.~
@1079 = ~[PC] You sound like Aerie.~
@1080 = ~[PC] Well, take your mind off of it. Tell me a story to distract from all this oppressive darkness.~
@1081 = ~[PC] Hey, Aran, I remember you telling a story... can you tell it to me again?~
@1082 = ~[PC] Angelo seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1083 = ~[PC] Anishai seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1084 = ~[PC] Azure seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1085 = ~[PC] Gavin seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1086 = ~[PC] Haldamir seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1087 = ~[ARAN] This place be like a great huge weight on me, pushin' down. I done heard o' bein' in th' bowels o' th' earth, but I never did think to be there myself.~ [c-aws076]
@1088 = ~[PC] Why do I think you are about to make some horrible childish intestine joke?~
@1089 = ~[PC] It is not a great time to talk right now, Aran. In fact, it is a lousy time, so shut up.~
@1090 = ~[PC] I was wondering what that smell was. I just assumed it was you.~
@1091 = ~[PC] You keep that depressing talk up, and we will have to do something to calm Aerie down.~
@1092 = ~[PC] Jonathan seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1093 = ~[PC] Chloe seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1094 = ~[PC] Alora seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1095 = ~[PC] Miriam seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1096 = ~[ARAN] So, you doin' anythin' fun tonight? I figure we could use some distraction from all this grimness an' darkness.~ [c-aws077]
@1097 = ~[PC] Err... Aran... look around. Do you really think this is a place with a nice corner pub we can go visit?~
@1098 = ~[PC] Actually, I thought I would go for a nice walk. Do you want to come along?~
@1099 = ~[PC] Oh, no you don't. I am not falling for that again. Last time, we ended up in a dice game that cost me dearly.~
@1100 = ~[PC] I think a cooking contest is in order. The secret ingredient will be... fungus!~
@1101 = ~[PC] Do I look like I am in the mood for talk of any kind?~
@1102 = ~[PC] We should do something to perk up Aerie. She seems to be very upset about being down here.~
@1103 = ~[PC] Nikita seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1104 = ~[PC] Ninafer seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1105 = ~[PC] Coran seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1106 = ~[PC] SilverStar seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1107 = ~[PC] Alassa seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1108 = ~[PC] Rylorn seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1109 = ~[PC] Saerileth seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1110 = ~[PC] Sime seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1111 = ~[PC] Bruce seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1112 = ~[PC] Neh'Taniel seems to be handling this better than you are.~
@1113 = ~[ARAN] Do you think it be sunny up topside today, or cloudy?~ [c-aws078]
@1114 = ~[PC] I don't care. I never bothered much with the weather anyways. I always was more of a city <PRO_GIRLBOY> than a country mouse.~
@1115 = ~[PC] It doesn't matter much, does it. I wonder if this place ever ends?~
@1116 = ~[PC] It is not a great time to talk right now, Aran.~
@1117 = ~[PC] Sunny, I bet. Hey, we should do something to perk up Aerie. She seems to be very upset about being down here.~
@1118 = ~[PC] Thinking about the sky is not going to help you down here. Take your mind off of it. Tell me a story to distract us from all this oppressive darkness.~
@1119 = ~[PC]Thinking about the sky is not going to help you down here. Take your mind off of it. Tell me a story to distract us from all this oppressive darkness.~
@1120 = ~[PC] I really don't want to follow that thought. It is too depressing. Hey, Aran, I remember you telling a story... can you tell it to me again?~
@1121 = ~[ARAN] Mayhap... well, mayhap there be some use in all this evil fungus-lovin' dark creepy ugliness. But me, I just don't rightly see why it don't all be put to th' torch, an' wiped out.~ [c-aws079]
@1122 = ~[PC] I am so sick of discussing deep thoughts. Come on, tell me a story.~
@1123 = ~[PC] There has to be something besides death and destruction to talk about. Come up with something else, please.~
@1124 = ~[PC] Now I did not expect you to say something like that. Wipe out all of Underdark, without pausing to see if some of the beings are simply trapped here? That doesn't sound like you.~
@1125 = ~[ARAN] Aye, that be strange.~ [c-aws086]
@1126 = ~[PC] What?~
@1127 = ~[PC] You do know you are murdering common tongue, right? Do you mean "That sword is strange", or "That rock looks strange", or something like that?~
@1128 = ~[PC] Do you find my choice of god strange, Aran, or are you just randomly commenting on our scenery?~
@1129 = ~[PC] Are you concerned about one of my spell components? Is something spilling out, or are you just randomly commenting on our scenery?~
@1130 = ~[PC] What, is my weapons gear slipping? What is catching your eye?~
@1131 = ~[PC] I am used to be called "strange", Aran, but not usually to my face. Or are you just randomly commenting on our scenery?~
@1132 = ~[PC] There is infinite strangeness in all things, Aran. Are we discussing something particular, or are you just randomly commenting on our scenery?~
@1133 = ~[PC] What is strange? I have been watching the whole area... or are you just randomly commenting on the universe?~
@1134 = ~[PC] Let me guess. You have noticed that the big guy with the rodent talks to himself once in awhile. Get over it, please - Minsc is a useful companion, despite his eccentricities.~
@1135 = ~[PC] I will take that as a compliment. You were talking about me, right?~
@1136 = ~[ARAN] Perhaps we should hire on a few more swords, an' make sure we have a bit more force up front, so to speak.~ [c-aws087]
@1137 = ~[PC] We seem to be holding our own. Why should we burden the party with more fighters?~
@1138 = ~[PC] Look, no talking. We are in a rush.~
@1139 = ~[PC] I may weave spells instead of swords, but we are doing well enough. What changes would you have me make?~
@1140 = ~[PC] Are you saying I am not enough of a fighter?~
@1141 = ~[PC] You may have a point. Things do not seem to be going well in combat. What would you suggest we do differently?~
@1142 = ~[PC] And here I thought you were a fighter, not a thinker. This might be amusing. Go on, then, oh great leader of combat, inform your betters as to combat tactics.~
@1143 = ~[ARAN] You know, when I was servin' in th' Flaming Fist just outside o' Cloakwood, we heard a few rumors about someone named <CHARNAME>. Never did hear what happened completely, but apparently <CHARNAME>'s adventurin' group took the head right off the Iron Throne, an' made our work considerably easier.~ [c-aws088]
@1144 = ~[PC] That would be me.~
@1145 = ~[PC] You don't say. That sounds like a fascinating person to meet. Did the rumors mention how stunning <PRO_HESHE> looked?~
@1146 = ~[PC] That is interesting. Did anyone say how strong <PRO_HESHE> was?~
@1147 = ~[PC] Hmmm. Did those rumors say anything about how nimble and quick <PRO_HESHE> was?~
@1148 = ~[PC] Hmmm. Did those rumors say anything about how hardy and resistant <PRO_HESHE> was?~
@1149 = ~[PC] Never heard of <PRO_HIMHER>.~
@1150 = ~[PC] Rumors. A bunch of hot air. But just out of idle curiosity, was there any mention of how brilliantly smart <PRO_HESHE> was?~
@1151 = ~[PC] I would not put much stoke in rumors. They throw more shadow than light.~
@1152 = ~[PC] Amazing how rumors start. Why just the other day, I heard something about how Aran Whitehand had a big fat mouth, and used it too often...~
@1153 = ~[ARAN] I know there be some disadvantages to bein' th' offspring o' a dead god, but there might just be a few advantages too, eh? I mean, you won't have to wait for no table at even th' finest establishments. An' those special powers come in right handy. There must be some reason Tymora flipped your coin this way. I mean, of all th' places on Toril, why did you be endin' up here?~
@1154 = ~[PC] I don't pray to Tymora, and I doubt that there is a religious reason for me to be here, unless you count a worship of raw power.~
@1155 = ~[PC] Magic. I suddenly appeared to the natives, and of course they recognized my Divine spirit immediately.~
@1156 = ~[PC] I was kidnapped and taken here against my will. They... no, he... Irenicus took my closest companion, and dispensed with most of my gear. On top of all that, I have to wander around in a gods-blighted country that has a serious problem with magic. So far, I don't see the positive in this.~
@1157 = ~[PC] I don't see how any of this is your business.~
@1158 = ~[PC] Tymora didn't flip my coin, Aran. She flipped yours. Why else would you be allowed the opportunity to be part of my adventures?~
@1159 = ~[PC] I don't really know which question I should answer. I think there were three in there.~
@1160 = ~[PC] Look, I don't want to talk about this right now. Actually, I think I never want to talk about this.~
@1161 = ~[ARAN] Hey, <CHARNAME>, how about a few extra coins on some right fine parchment next time we see someplace to get a mite o' supplies?~ [c-aws089]
@1162 = ~[PC] That depends. What is in it for me?~
@1163 = ~[PC] You already spend way too much time scribbling and muttering with a pen in your mouth when you should be resting, Aran.~
@1164 = ~[PC] Why do you waste your time puttering on that parchment every night, instead of working on your weapons skills?~
@1165 = ~[PC] Absolutely. Do you mind me asking what you want it for?~
@1166 = ~[PC] No. And stop talking to me.~
@1167 = ~[ARAN] So, what do it be like, to be th' center of attention?~
@1168 = ~[PC] I don't know what you mean.~
@1169 = ~[PC] I suspect you were always the center of attention.~
@1170 = ~[PC] No one ever notices me, and I like it that way.~
@1171 = ~[PC] I don't mind being the center of attention. At least, not the center of your attention.~
@1172 = ~[PC] It is great. I get all the best adversaries tring to kill me, and I never have to wait for dinner reservations.~
@1173 = ~[ARAN] Wait up a second an' let a lad get a breather, eh? I think this be a good time for me to take stock o' th' situation, so to speak.~
@1174 = ~[ARAN] Hey, You ever study tactics an' such?~ [c-aws090]
@1175 = ~[PC] Yes, I have. Is there something wrong with what I am doing in combat?~
@1176 = ~[PC] No, I have never studied tactics. I am learning as I go along.~
@1177 = ~[PC] Aran... to borrow one of your colorful phrases, "Cyric's Black Heart, shut the nine hells up".~
@1178 = ~[PC] Why study, when I have you to stand in front of me and act as a meat shield?~
@1179 = ~[PC] Tactics and strategy, planning and plotting... all useless. I just dive into each fight and see if we survive.~
@1180 = ~[ARAN] There be a mite o' difference between chasin' around Faerun in pursuit o' treasure, fame, an' such, an' chasin' around Faerun close on th' tail o' adversaries what can call on th' powers this 'Irenicus' bastard can.~ [c-aws091]
@1181 = ~[PC] Are you in this for fame, fortune, and riches beyond your wildest imagination?~
@1182 = ~[PC] You talk too much.~
@1183 = ~[PC] Irenicus is a means to an end. To be more precise and borrow your quaint speech patterns, I means to end him.~
@1184 = ~[PC] I do not have much choice in the matter.~
@1185 = ~[PC] Sune abhors ugliness. I think that in this case, my personal needs and my goddess's' needs are one and the same.~
@1186 = ~[ARAN] Tempus' Toasty Toes, that tears it.~
@1187 = ~[ARAN] I have naught in th' way o' figurin' how so many creatures get in your way. There be a fair number of things what have challenged you so far, an' they all done lost. At some point you'd think they would just stand aside, on account o' not wantin' to be crushed.~
@1188 = ~[PC] It would be better for them if they took your advice.~
@1189 = ~[PC] I do not "crush' those that stand in my path. I defend myself, and I try to do what is necessary.~
@1190 = ~[PC] Oh, now there is an idea. I'll send you on ahead and you can tell them "stand aside! <CHARNAME> is coming through!".~
@1191 = ~[PC] I am not happy so many have lost their lives, but most of adventuring seems to be about combat.~
@1192 = ~[PC] You do not become an adventurer if you shrink from battle.~
@1193 = ~[PC] I think I would rather just carry on with what we are doing, and not have a long philosophical discussion right now.~
@1194 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. Not everythin' can be dealt with wi' a wave o' magic, so it might help you, too.~
@1195 = ~[PC] I am not sure I want to do that, Aran. My best combat is done through casting spells.~
@1196 = ~[PC] That sounds like a great idea. Let's do it.~
@1197 = ~[PC] Waving pointy things at each other randomly during the middle of an adventure... what could possibly go wrong?~
@1198 = ~[PC] Well... I suppose...~
@1199 = ~[PC] I am not sure this is the time or place, Aran. Perhaps we should find somewhere more protected.~
@1200 = ~[PC] I prefer you when you are the silent type. Right now, obviously, this is a problem, because you keep opening your mouth and letting wind come out.~
@1201 = ~[PC] Please, keep talking. I always yawn when I am interested. Just in case you did not notice, this is called 'sarcasm'.~
@1202 = ~[PC] Silence. That is spelled 's i l e n c e'. You are a scribe - write it down, and post it somewhere where you can read it.~
@1203 = ~[PC] I don't mind you talking so much, as long as you don't mind me not listening.~
@1204 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. You have a few moves what might be good to learn, too. I can always use another fighter's perspective, eh?~
@1205 = ~[PC] That sounds like a good idea to me. Where do you want to set up? Do you favor Waterdeep Twin swords style, or Moonshae Axes? I have been wanting to try some new combinations.~
@1206 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. Not everythin' can be dealt with wi' a prayer an' a spell, so it might help you, too.~
@1207 = ~[PC] I could use some weapons practice. I will even say a prayer for you, Aran, for when you find yourself on the losing end of the skirmish.~
@1208 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. Not everythin' can be hid from or taken down at range, so it might help you, too.~
@1209 = ~[PC] Would you like to use your dagger? Because I just lifted it off of you, so you would have to ask for it back.~
@1210 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. Music may sooth savage beasts, but some o' them might just decide they are happy enough to take a chunk out o' us, so it might help you, too.~
@1211 = ~[PC] I would prefer a duel of wits, or perhaps song and poem. But if you would like to try a skirmish, I can oblige you.~
@1212 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. You fight fair too many times, an' I don't, so it might help you, too.~
@1213 = ~[PC] A noble thought. It would be good practice. Where would you like to set up this session?~
@1214 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. You have to split your time between th' magic study an' th' weapons practice, so it might help you, too.~
@1215 = ~[PC] I suppose I need to stay with the weapons side of things, and not cast any spells, right? Oh, if it will make you better at your job, sure.~
@1216 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. Fightin' an' prayin' at th' same time takes a good bit o' concentration, I bet, so it might help you, too.~
@1217 = ~[PC] My fighting skills are sharp, as is my faith, Aran. But if you need some practice, I will help you.~
@1218 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. A straightforward fight, too, not all that fancy slippery dexterous crap you usually pull. I be a fighter, not an acrobat, by Sune's Smile.~
@1219 = ~[PC] My fighting skills are sharp enough, Aran, but sure. I will even wager this purse that I will win.~
@1220 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. You split your skills up to a large extent, so it might help you drill down some o' your fightin' moves.~
@1221 = ~[PC] Well, I could use a little practice. Between practicing picking locks, casting spells, and weapons cleaning there is never enough time for a good skirmish.~
@1222 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. But go on th' magic or callin' any woodland allies, or any o' that shapeshiftin', eh? Just a good clean spar.~
@1223 = ~[PC] It is part of nature's beauty that the animal form should be trained and used as efficiently as possible. Perhaps we should schedule several training sessions together.~
@1224 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. Not everythin' can be dealt with at range, so it might help you, too. Though I'd best be on my guard. You rangers all seem trained up in usin' more than one weapon at a time.~
@1225 = ~[PC] We could spar. I think I should teach you a bit more about tracking, though.~
@1226 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. Wi' all that magic, an' th' careful work on locks an' such, I figure you might need a mite bit o' practice on combat.~
@1227 = ~[PC] Well, since I just pick-pocketed your dagger and made it invisible, why not make the first challenge you finding your dagger?~
@1228 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. Come on, it will be a right fine change o' pace for you.~
@1229 = ~[PC] I could pray to the gods to help you, or cast a healing spell. Or we could try a small training exercise. But magic is really my strong point, Aran.~
@1230 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. No prayers for help from beyond, an' no slippery tricks... just a straight fight.~
@1231 = ~[PC] We could, but my faith has allowed me a unique opportunity. My prayers have been answered, and voila... is this your dagger?~
@1232 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. No callin' in any extra help, though. Let's stick to th' standard fightin' work we both need brushin' up on.~
@1233 = ~[PC] A good warmup helps everyone. But I should really teach you more about tracking.~
@1234 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. You need it. Too much divided attention, eh? Let's postulate you done ran out o' divine an' arcane spells, an' just need to whack th' crap out o' th' enemy.~
@1235 = ~[PC] My skills are divided between arcane, spiritual, and physical pursuits, Aran. But I suppose that I have time to indulge in one of the three.~
@1236 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. You might learn somethin' from doin' things other than talkin' to gods an' animals an' trees an' whatnot.~
@1237 = ~[PC] The gods help those who help themselves, Aran, so I would be happy to practice with you. I should teach you some tracking skills, though.~
@1238 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. Not everythin' can be dealt with wi' a wave o' magic, so it might help you, too. Think o' it as backup for when th' magical energies just don't rightly want to flow for you, eh?~
@1239 = ~[PC] Well, I do not practice the way you do, Aran. But some minor skirmishing might sharpen us. I will just have to be careful and not accidentally turn you into a cinder.~
@1240 = ~[ARAN] We have a moment, <CHARNAME>. You want to take a bit o' time an' spar here? I could use some limberin' up. Besides, I be right fascinated. I done heard some o' you monks can catch a man's blade out o' the air wi' your bare hands.~
@1241 = ~[PC] A good idea. No weapons, though.~
@1242 = ~[PC] Fighting you might be a change of pace. Being better than you, well, that is a habit.~
@1243 = ~[ARAN] You be a mite late, there, <CHARNAME>. I was just about to turn in, eh?~ [c-aws093]
@1244 = ~[PC] I think the bet was 5 gold that you would lose, 10 gold that you would trip on something during the match, and no takers on how many times you would swear.~
@1245 = ~[PC] You look like you have been working hard already. Do you want to postpone this? I do not want to take advantage of your fatigue.~
@1246 = ~[PC] Think of it as early for tomorrow. The moon is still up, so there is plenty of light, and I am here now.~
@1247 = ~[PC] I think I would rather not spar tonight, Aran. I am going to turn in.~
@1248 = ~[PC] Look, if you were an attractive young female, I would have been here hours ago. Consider yourself lucky I showed up at all.~
@1249 = ~[PC] Do you always spar with your shirt off?~
@1250 = ~[PC] Judging from the sheen of sweat on your chest, it looks like you have been working hard. Do you want to postpone this?~
@1251 = ~[PC] Think of it as early for tomorrow. The moon is still up, and I am here now.~
@1252 = ~[PC] You are a little slow, aren't you. When I said 'spar', I was thinking of more amorous pursuits.~
@1253 = ~[ARAN] We keep runnin' around, battling' various foes, an' collectin' artifacts, treasures, an' knowledge. Cyric's Dark Heart, do you think we are ever goin' to slow down? Or ever just claim victory?~ [c-aws095]
@1254 = ~[PC] I think that we shall prevail. After all, we have made it this far. Things should be getting better any day now.~
@1255 = ~[PC] I do not think we shall survive this. Fighting against so many foes, for so long, how can the outcome be anything but death and destruction?~
@1256 = ~[PC] Perhaps we shall win. Perhaps we shall lose. But really, we don't have much of a choice in the matter. The fates decide our destiny.~
@1257 = ~[PC] We are here. We have not lost yet. Speculating on the future just wastes our time and energy.~
@1258 = ~[PC] That depends. Are you worried that you're running out of oaths?~
@1259 = ~[PC] Now is not a good time to talk, Aran.~
@1260 = ~[PC] Can we move along?~
@1261 = ~[PC] Silence is golden. Pay yourself.~
@1262 = ~[ARAN] Hey, I been thinkin'.~ [c-aws096]
@1263 = ~[PC] Not a good time, Aran. No more talking.~
@1264 = ~[PC] Cut the chatter, Aran. We need to move along.~
@1265 = ~[PC] And I have been thinking, too. Mostly about how to get you to stop talking.~
@1266 = ~[PC] What is on your mind, Aran?~
@1267 = ~[PC] Praise be to the gods. I am finally getting you to use the gifts the gods granted you!~
@1268 = ~[PC] Praise be to Talos. I am finally getting you to use the gifts the Storms can bring you!~
@1269 = ~[PC] Helm has granted my deepest prayers on your behalf. May His Shield guard your new endeavors!~
@1270 = ~[PC] The God of new beginnings is very kind. A new day dawns for you, Aran!~
@1271 = ~[PC] Moving in on my territory? I thought you were better suited to action, rather than thought.~
@1272 = ~[PC] Are you sure that is wise? So far, I have been the one casing the joint and making the plans. What is all this about 'thinking'?~
@1273 = ~[PC] I knew you had it in you, Aran. Now we just need to work on your singing voice, and you may have the beginnings of true bardship.~
@1274 = ~[PC] I thought that was just the remnants of last night's dinner lingering in the air.~
@1275 = ~[ARAN] Hey, <CHARNAME>. Tell me a story, eh? Somethin' to take th' edge off all o' this blood an' death an' such.~ [c-aws097]
@1276 = ~[PC] I do not have any stories to tell. How about you tell me one.~
@1277 = ~[PC] Do I look like a bard? Wait a minute... yes, I do. Sure, I will tell you a story. What kind of story do you want to hear?~
@1278 = ~[PC] Do I look like a bard?~
@1279 = ~[PC] I would be glad to tell you a story. Do you want a true story, or an invented one?~
@1280 = ~[PC] Aren't you supposed to be talking to me seriously about the nature of existence, or giving me some deep advice about surviving all this?~
@1281 = ~[PC] I do not know, Aran. All I seem to be able to think about is doom and gloom.~
@1282 = ~[ARAN] Somethin' wrong?~
@1283 = ~[PC] Nothing.~
@1284 = ~[PC] Everything.~
@1285 = ~[PC] Something.~
@1286 = ~[PC] Shut up.~
@1287 = ~[PC] Go away.~
